cal Services Administration\n| accessdate = 23 September 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Demographics==\n\n{{Philippine Census\n| cols = 2\n| align= none\n| title= Population census of Baler\n| 1903 = 2417\n| 1918 = 3413\n| 1939 = 11887\n| 1948 = 17182\n| 1960 = 10350\n| 1970 = 14632\n| 1975 = 16046\n| 1980 = 18349\n| 1990 = 24689\n| 1995 = 26919\n| 2000 = 29923\n| 2007 = 34492\n| 2010 = 36010\n| 2015 = 39562\n| 2020 =\n| 2025 =\n| 2030 =\n| footnote= Source: [[Philippine Statistics Authority]]{{PH census|2015}}{{PH census|2010}}{{PH census|2007}}{{LWUA population data}} \n}}\n\nPeople with connections to the town are referred to as Balerenos. Prior to the arrival of Spanish missionaries in Baler in 1609, settlements by [[Aeta people]] and [[Ilongot]] in Baler's coast and mountain areas already exists. [[Tagalog people|Tagalogs]], some originating from [[Palanan]] and [[Infanta, Quezon]], came in to the area to trade by boat. Some Tagalogs settled in Baler and married with the Aeta and Ilongots.<ref name=Aurorapeople>{{cite web|last1=Mesina|first1=Ilovita|title=Baler And Its People, The Aurorans|url=http://www.aurora.ph/baler-aurora-book/baler-and-its-people.html|website=Aurora.ph|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Spanish brought in Filipino acolytes from other areas of Luzon from 1609 to 1899. During this period, Baler can only be access by sea though the town saw increase migration from other parts of Luzon such as [[Laguna (province)|Laguna]], [[Tayabas]], and [[Bicol Region|Bicol]] from the south. The opening of the Baler-Bongabon Road allowed easier migration of people from [[Ilocos Region|Ilocos]] and [[Isabela (province)|Isabela]] areas from the north. The road also allowed [[Igorot people]] and [[Batangas|Batangue\u00f1os]] to settle in Baler.<ref name=Aurorapeople/>\n\nIn the {{PH wikidata|population_as_of}}, Baler had a population of {{PH wikidata|population_total}}.{{PH census|current}} The population density was {{convert|{{sigfig|{{PH wikidata|population_total}}/{{PH wikidata|area}}|2}}|PD/km2}}.\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Local government==\n[[File:Baler Municipal Hall.jpg|thumb|Baler Municipal Hall]]\nThe Current Officials of Baler, Aurora (as of May 19, 2019)<ref>{{cite web|title=Government Officials of Aurora, Philippines|url=http://www.aurora.ph/officials.html|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Designation\n|-\n| Angara, Rhett Ronan || Mayor\n|-\n| Ong, Bobong || Vice Mayor\n|-\n| Valenzuela, Pandus || Member Sangguniang Bayan\n|-\n| Galban, Manny || Member Sangguniang Bayan\n|-\n| Ong, Danilo || Member Sangguniang Bayan\n|-\n| Guerrero, Santino Rosauro || Member Sangguniang Bayan\n|-\n| Morillo, Eto || Member Sangguniang Bayan\n|-\n| Buluag, Edith || Member Sangguniang Bayan\n|-\n| Zubia, Francisco III || Member Sangguniang Bayan\n|-\n| Villacorte, Ellah || Member Sangguniang Bayan\n|}\n\n==Culture==\nBaler annually observes the [[Philippine\u2013Spanish Friendship Day]] which commemorates the end of the historic [[Siege of Baler]]<ref name=\"rpspain1\">{{cite news|last1=Galvez|first1=Manny|title=RP-Spain Friendship Day marked today in Bale|url=https://beta.philstar.com/nation/2010/07/02/589112/rp-spain-friendship-day-marked-today-baler|accessdate=21 February 2018|work=The Philippine Star|date=2 July 2010}}</ref> and celebrates [[Philippines\u2013Spain relations]] developed since then.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Quismundo|first1=Tarra|title=Filipino, Spanish officials mark Friendship Day in Baler, Aurora|url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/140677/filipino-spanish-officials-mark-friendship-day-in-baler-quezon|accessdate=21 February 2018|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=5 July 2016}}</ref> It is usually held every June 30 and the rites which was first done in the provincial capital has also been observed in other parts of the country as well as parts of Spain.<ref name=\"rpspain1\"/>\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Manuel L. Quezon]], first [[President of the Philippines|President]] of the [[Commonwealth of the Philippines]]\n* [[Aurora Quezon]], former First Lady of the Philippines, wife of Commonwealth President Manuel L. Quezon\n* [[Eunice Pablo Guerrero-Cucueco]], the first female governor of Aurora province\n* Loreto Bihasa, a veteran whose exploits in the [[Korean War]] was made into a movie starring [[Vic Vargas]]\n* [[Edgardo Angara]], former Senate President, former [[University of the Philippines]] president and longest-serving senator in the Philippines.\n* [[Bella Angara]], the first and the only woman in the history of the Philippine Congress to become house majority floor leader\n* [[Sonny Angara]], one of the recipients of the Ten Outstanding Young Men (TOYM) Awards for 2010, who received his trophy from President [[Benigno Aquino III]], former President of the Philippines.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed heights=100px>  <!-- Add additional image only to Commons category:Baler, Aurora  -->\nFile:Baler Public Market in Aurora province.jpg|Baler Public Market\nFile:Sabang2jf.JPG|Outer Banks, Labasin{{nbhyph}}Sabang Beach\nFile:Erm8jf.jpg|View of [[Baler Bay]] from Ermita Hill\nFile:DigisitLukso2jf.jpg|Rocky islets in Diguisit Bay\nFile:Dicasalarin Cove.jpg|Dicasalarin Cove\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Baler}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.batangbaler.net Batang Baler]\n* [http://www.aurora.ph/baler.html Aurora, Philippines \u2013 Baler]\n\n{{Geographic location\n| Centre    = Baler\n| North     = [[Dipaculao, Aurora|Dipaculao]]\n| Northeast = ''[[Baler&nbsp;Bay]]''\n| East      = ''[[Philippine&nbsp;Sea]]''\n| South     = [[San Luis, Aurora|San&nbsp;Luis]]\n| West      = [[Maria Aurora, Aurora|Maria&nbsp;Aurora]]\n}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Articles related to Baler, Aurora\n| state = uncollapsed\n| list  = \n{{Aurora|state=expanded}}\n{{Central Luzon}}\n{{Philippine Provincial Capitals}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Municipalities of Aurora (province)]]\n[[Category:Provincial capitals of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Surfing locations in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1609]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                   = {{PH wikidata|name}}\n| image_skyline          = Baleraurora.jpg\n| image_caption          = Poblacion Area of Baler\n| image_seal             = Ph seal aurora baler.png\n| image_map              = {{PH wikidata|image_map}}\n| map_caption            = {{PH wikidata|map_caption}}\n| image_map1             = {{hidden begin|title=OpenStreetMap|ta1=center}}{{Infobox mapframe|id={{#invoke:Wikibase|id}}|frame-width=250}}{{hidden end}}\n| pushpin_map            = Philippines\n| pushpin_label_position = right\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location within the {{PH wikidata|country}}\n| coordinates            = {{PH wikidata|coordinates}}\n| settlement_type        = {{PH wikidata|settlement_type}}\n| subdivision_type       = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name       = {{flag|Philippines}}\n| subdivision_type1      = [[Regions of the Philippines|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1      = {{PH wikidata|region}}\n| subdivision_type2      = [[Provinces of the Philippines|Province]]\n| subdivision_name2      = [[Aurora (province)|Aurora]]\n| official_name          = {{PH wikidata|official_name}}\n| native_name            =\n| other_name             =\n| nickname               =\n| motto                  =\n| anthem                 =\n| subdivision_type3      = [[House of Representatives of the Philippines#District representation|District]]\n| subdivision_name3      = [[Legislative district of Aurora|Lone District]]\n| established_title      = Founded\n| established_date       = 19 August 1609\n| parts_type             = [[Barangay]]s\n| parts_style            = para\n| p1                     = 13 (see [[#Barangays|Barangays]])\n| leader_title           = {{PH wikidata|leader_title}} <!--mayor-->\n| leader_name            = Rhett Ronan T. Angara  \n| leader_title1          = [[Vice Mayor]]\n| leader_name1           = Pedro M. Ong, Jr.  \n| leader_title2          = Congressman\n| leader_name2           = Rommel Rico T. Angara\n| leader_title3          = [[Sangguniang Panlalawigan|SP Board member]]\n| leader_name3           = \n| leader_title4          = Electorate \n| leader_name4           = {{PH wikidata|electorate}} voters ([[Philippine general election, {{PH wikidata|electorate_point_in_time}}|{{PH wikidata|electorate_point_in_time}}]])\n| government_type        = {{PH wikidata|government_type}}\n| government_footnotes   = {{thinsp}}<ref>{{DILG detail}}</ref>\n| elevation_footnotes    =\n| elevation_m            =\n| area_footnotes         = {{PSGC detail|area}}\n| area_total_km2         = {{PH wikidata|area}}\n| population_footnotes   = {{PH census|current}}\n| population_total       = {{PH wikidata|population_total}}\n| population_as_of       = {{PH wikidata|population_as_of}}\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| population_demonym     =\n| population_rank        =\n| population_note        =\n| timezone               = [[Philippine Standard Time|PST]]\n| utc_offset             = +8\n| postal_code_type       = [[List of ZIP codes in the Philippines|ZIP code]]\n| postal_code            = {{PH wikidata|postal_code}}\n| postal2_code_type      = {{PSGCstyle}}\n| postal2_code           = {{PSGC detail}}\n| area_code_type         = {{areacodestyle}}\n| area_code              = {{PH wikidata|area_code}}\n| website                = {{PH wikidata|website}}\n| demographics_type1     = Economy\n| demographics1_title1   = {{PH wikidata|income_class_title}}\n| demographics1_info1    = {{PH wikidata|income_class}}\n| demographics1_title2   = [[Measuring poverty|Poverty incidence]]\n| demographics1_info2    = 9.13% (2015)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://psa.gov.ph/sites/default/files/City%20and%20Municipal-level%20Small%20Area%20Poverty%20Estimates_%202009%2C%202012%20and%202015_0.xlsx|title=PSA releases the 2015 Municipal and City Level Poverty Estimates|location=Quezon City, Philippines |accessdate=12 October 2019}}</ref>\n| demographics1_title3   = Revenue (\u20b1)\n| demographics1_info3    = {{PH wikidata|revenue}} {{PH wikidata|revenue_point_in_time}} \n| demographics1_title4   = Revenue Rank\n| demographics1_info4    = \n| demographics1_title5   = Assets (\u20b1)\n| demographics1_info5    = {{PH wikidata|assets}} {{PH wikidata|assets_point_in_time}} \n| demographics1_title6   = Assets Rank\n| demographics1_info6    = \n| demographics1_title7   = Liabilities (\u20b1)\n| demographics1_info7    = {{PH wikidata|liabilities}} {{PH wikidata|liabilities_point_in_time}} \n| demographics1_title8   = Liabilities Rank\n| demographics1_info8    = \n| demographics1_title9   = Expenditure (\u20b1)\n| demographics1_info9    = {{PH wikidata|expenditure}} {{PH wikidata|expenditure_point_in_time}} \n| demographics1_title10  = Expenditure Rank\n| demographics1_info10   = \n| demographics_type2     = \n| demographics2_title1   = Electricity\n| demographics2_info1    =  \n| demographics2_title2   = Water\n| demographics2_info2    =  \n| demographics2_title3   = Telecommunications\n| demographics2_info3    = \n| demographics2_title4   = Cable TV\n| demographics2_info4    =\n| demographics2_title5   = \n| demographics2_info5    =\n| demographics2_title6   = \n| demographics2_info6    =\n| demographics2_title7   = \n| demographics2_info7    =\n| demographics2_title8   = \n| demographics2_info8    =\n| demographics2_title9   = \n| demographics2_info9    =\n| demographics2_title10  = \n| demographics2_info10   =\n| blank_name_sec1        = {{PH wikidata|climate_title}}\n| blank_info_sec1        = {{PH wikidata|climate_type}}\n| blank1_name_sec1       = Native languages\n| blank1_info_sec1       = {{PH wikidata|language}}\n| blank2_name_sec1       = Sister localities\n| blank2_info_sec1       = \n| blank3_name_sec1       = \n| blank3_info_sec1       = \n| blank4_name_sec1       = \n| blank4_info_sec1       = \n| blank5_name_sec1       = \n| blank5_info_sec1       = \n| blank6_name_sec1       = \n| blank6_info_sec1       = \n| blank7_name_sec1       = \n| blank7_info_sec1       = \n| blank1_name_sec2       = Major religions\n| blank1_info_sec2       = \n| blank2_name_sec2       = Feast date\n| blank2_info_sec2       = \n| blank3_name_sec2       = Catholic diocese\n| blank3_info_sec2       =\n| blank4_name_sec2       = Patron saint \n| blank4_info_sec2       = \n| blank5_name_sec2       = \n| blank5_info_sec2       = \n| blank6_name_sec2       = \n| blank6_info_sec2       = \n| blank7_name_sec2       = \n| blank7_info_sec2       =\n| short_description      =\n| footnotes              =\n}}\n\n'''{{PH wikidata|name}}''', officially the '''{{PH wikidata|official_name}}''' ({{lang-tl|Bayan ng Baler}}; {{lang-ilo|Ili ti Baler}}), is a [[{{PH wikidata|settlement_text}} of the Philippines|{{PH wikidata|settlement_text}}]] and capital of the [[province of the Philippines|province]] of [[Aurora (province)|Aurora]], {{PH wikidata|country}}. According to the {{PH wikidata|population_as_of}}, it has a population of {{PH wikidata|population_total}} people.{{PH census|current}}\n\nBaler is located {{convert|231|km}} north-east of [[Manila]] via a mountain pass accessible by bus and private vehicle. It is host to spectacular geographic formations and is situated on a vast plain at the south end of [[Baler Bay]], a contiguous segment of the [[Philippine Sea]].\n\nIt became the capital of Aurora on 14 June 1951 under ''[[Republic Act]] No. 648''<ref name=\"ChanRobles-RA648\">{{cite web|title=Republic Act No. 648 - An Act Creating The Subprovince Of Aurora, Which Shall Comprise The Municipalities Of Baler, Casiguran, Dipaculao And Maria Aurora, Province Of Quezon|url=http://www.chanrobles.com/republicacts/republicactno648.html|website=Chan Robles Virtual Law Library|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424100810/http://www.chanrobles.com/republicacts/republicactno648.html#.WB1ufdV97IU|archivedate=24 April 2016|date=14 June 1951}}</ref> signed by President [[Elpidio Quirino]]. It remained the seat of government of Aurora on 21 November 1978 under ''Batas Pambansa Blg. 7''<ref name=\"ChanRobles-BP7\">{{cite web|title=Batas Pambansa Blg. 7 - An Act Separating the Sub-Province of Aurora from the Province of Quezon and Establishing It as an Independent Province|url=http://www.chanrobles.com/bataspambansa/bataspambansablg7.html|website=Chan Robles Virtual Law Library|accessdate=5 November 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303185029/http://www.chanrobles.com/bataspambansa/bataspambansablg7.html#.WB1vb9V97IW|archivedate=3 March 2016|date=21 November 1978}}</ref> signed by President [[Ferdinand Marcos]].\n\n==History==\n{{More citations needed section|date=November 2016}}\n\n===Spanish colonial period===\n[[File:Las tropas del teniente coronel Tecs\u00f3n en Baler (mayo de 1899, La Ilustraci\u00f3n Art\u00edstica, M. Arias y Rodr\u00edguez).jpg|thumb|left|Filipino troops of Colonel Tecson in Baler (May 1899)]]\n\nIn 1609, seven [[Franciscans|Franciscan missionaries]], led by Fray Blas Palomino, founded the settlement of Baler, which was later converted into a ''pueblo'' (town) by the [[Augustinians]] and the [[Recollects]] in 1658. Due to scarcity of religious missionaries, the Franciscans again took over the administration of the settlement in 1703.\n\nOn 27 December 1735, a great storm came and a huge wave called ''tromba marina'' devastated the old town settlement, then located in Barrio Sabang. Among the survivors were the Angaras, Bijasas, Bitongs, Lumasacs, Carrascos, and Pobletes who swam toward the nearby Ermita Hill.<ref>{{cite web |author=GOVPH |url=http://www.nhcp.gov.ph/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=160 |title=National Historical Commission of the Philippines - \"A Filipino society with citizens informed of their history, who love their country and are proud of their cultural heritage.\" |website=Nhcp.gov.ph |date= |accessdate=5 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514022856/http://www.nhcp.gov.ph/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=160 |archive-date=14 May 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=November 2016}} A new community sprang into what is now the Poblacion of Baler, leaving \"Kinagunasan,\" the place of devastation. A mural depicting this wave can be found in the Museo de Baler in town.{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\n[[File:Iglesia de San Luis de Tolosa de Baler, Aurora, Filipinas.jpg|thumb|San Luis Obispo de Tolosa Church]]\nOn 27 June 1898, 15 days after the [[Philippine Declaration of Independence]], 54 Spanish soldiers of the Baler garrison, under the command of Captain Enrique de las Morenas y Fossi, made San Luis Obispo de Tolosa Church, named in Spanish for [[Louis of Toulouse]], their barracks. When de las Morenas died on 22 November 1898, Lieutenant Saturnino Mart\u00edn Cerezo replaced him. On 2 June 1899, the last Spanish garrison in the Philippines surrendered after the [[Siege of Baler]], effectively ending over 300 years of Spanish rule in the country.<ref name=\"SpanAmWar-BalerSiege\">{{cite web|last1=Hernandez|first1=Miguel|title=The Last Action of the Spanish American War: The Siege of Baler|url=http://spanamwar.com/Baler.html|website=The Spanish American War Centennial Website|accessdate=5 November 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160730202411/http://spanamwar.com/Baler.html|archivedate=30 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===American colonial period===\nIn 1901, the Americans incorporated the town into the province of Tayabas (later named [[Quezon]] province). Before the Americans came, Baler was under the district of El Pr\u00edncipe.\n\nThe ''Comedia de Baler'' of Aurora mounted its first production in 1927. It was supported by then President [[Manuel L. Quezon]] and enjoyed the collaboration of artists Fortunato Esore\u00f1a and Alejandro Ferreras and arnis expert Antonino Ramos. Still alive until today, it features a group of colorfully attired performers using authentic weapons, like swords and knives, in their plays.\n\n===Japanese occupation===\nIn 1942, the [[Imperial Japanese Army]] entered Baler, where they made the Baler Elementary School building as their garrison under the command of a certain Captain Hattori. The general headquarters and camp base of the Philippine Commonwealth Army from 3 January 1942 to 30 June 1946 and the Philippine Constabulary from 28 October 1944 to 30 June 1946 were stationed in Baler. In 1945, Filipino and American troops landed in Baler, including Filipino troops of the 3rd Infantry Division, the 5th Infantry Division, the 51st Infantry Division, and the 52nd Infantry Division of the Philippine Commonwealth Army, the 5th Constabulary Regiment of the [[Philippine Constabulary]], the local recognized guerrilla unit, and the American troops of the [[6th Infantry Division (United States)|6th Infantry Division]] of the [[United States Army]]. The retreating Japanese troops destroyed the San Luis Obispo de Tolosa Church in Baler.{{citation needed|date=October 2011}}\n\n===Post-war period===\nOn 14 June 1951, by virtue of ''Republic Act No. 648'', Baler became the capital town of the sub-province (and later, province) of [[Aurora (province)|Aurora]].<ref name=\"PhilippineLawInfo-RA648\">{{cite web|title=Republic Act No. 648; An Act Creating the Subprovince of Aurora, Which Shall Comprise the Municipalities of Baler, Casiguran, Dipaculao and Maria Aurora, Province of Quezon|url=http://philippinelaw.info/statutes/ra648.html|website=PhilippineLaw.info|accessdate=5 November 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503122110/http://philippinelaw.info/statutes/ra648.html|archivedate=3 May 2012|date=14 June 1951}}</ref>\n\nIn 1956, the ''barrio'' of [[Dingalan]] was converted into a municipal district within Baler and later became a town in its right.<ref name=\"PhilippineLawInfo-RA1536\">{{cite web|title=Republic Act No. 1536; An Act Creating the Municipal District of Dingalan in the Municipality of Baler, Subprovince of Aurora, Province of Quezon|url=http://philippinelaw.info/statutes/ra1536.html|website=PhilippineLaw.info|accessdate=5 November 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503122100/http://philippinelaw.info/statutes/ra1536.html|archivedate=3 May 2012|date=16 June 1956}}</ref>\n\nIn 1976-7 the helicopter attack and surfing sequences of the film ''[[Apocalypse Now]]'' were filmed at Baler. The film is credited with having created the Philippines [[Surfing]] culture and the headland at Baler is known as \"Charlie's Point\" from a line in the film.<ref>{{cite news|title=How Apocalypse Now inspired Filipino surfers|publisher=BBC News|author=Kate McGeown|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-21941069|date=16 April 2013|accessdate=26 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[Philippine Statistics Authority]], the {{PH wikidata|settlement_text}} has a land area of {{convert|{{PH wikidata|area}}|km2}}{{PSGC detail|area}} constituting {{percentage|{{PH wikidata|area}}|{{PH wikidata|area|Q13730}}|2|pad=yes}} of the {{convert|{{PH wikidata|area|Q13730}}|km2|2|adj=mid|-}} total area of Aurora.\n\n===Barangays===\nBaler is politically subdivided into 13 barangays.{{PSGC detail|nscb}}\n\n{{PH brgy table lite|top}}\n{{PH brgy table lite|037701001| Barangay I (''[[Poblacion]]'') |  587|  717}}\n{{PH brgy table lite|037701002| Barangay II (''Poblacion'')    |  312|  374}}\n{{PH brgy table lite|037701003| Barangay III (''Poblacion'')   |  357|  434}}\n{{PH brgy table lite|037701004| Barangay IV (''Poblacion'')    |  363|  389}}\n{{PH brgy table lite|037701005| Barangay V (''Poblacion'')     | 1718| 1662}}\n{{PH brgy table lite|037701006| Buhangin                       | 5310| 5057}}\n{{PH brgy table lite|037701007| Calabuanan                     | 3895| 3221}}\n{{PH brgy table lite|037701008| Obligacion                     | 1215| 1135}}\n{{PH brgy table lite|037701009| Pingit                         | 5913| 4989}}\n{{PH brgy table lite|037701010| Reserva                        | 4580| 4064}}\n{{PH brgy table lite|037701011| Sabang                         | 4833| 4829}}\n{{PH brgy table lite|037701012| Suclayin                       | 6341| 5923}}\n{{PH brgy table lite|037701013| Zabali                         | 4138| 3216}}\n{{PH brgy table lite|bottom|36010}}\n\n===Climate===\n{{Weather box\n| location = Baler, Aurora (1995\u20132010, extremes 1949\u20132012)\n| metric first = Y\n| single line  = Y\n| Jan record high C = 33.3\n| Feb record high C = 35.0\n| Mar record high C = 35.8\n| Apr record high C = 37.5\n| May record high C = 38.6\n| Jun record high C = 38.8\n| Jul record high C = 41.2\n| Aug record high C = 37.0\n| Sep record high C = 37.0\n| Oct record high C = 35.5\n| Nov record high C = 34.2\n| Dec record high C = 33.9\n|year record high C = 41.2\n| Jan high C = 27.6\n| Feb high C = 28.3\n| Mar high C = 29.6\n| Apr high C = 30.9\n| May high C = 31.0\n| Jun high C = 31.4\n| Jul high C = 31.1\n| Aug high C = 31.2\n| Sep high C = 31.2\n| Oct high C = 30.5\n| Nov high C = 29.4\n| Dec high C = 27.8\n|year high C = 30.0\n| Jan mean C = 24.5\n| Feb mean C = 24.9\n| Mar mean C = 25.9\n| Apr mean C = 27.1\n| May mean C = 27.4\n| Jun mean C = 27.9\n| Jul mean C = 27.6\n| Aug mean C = 27.8\n| Sep mean C = 27.6\n| Oct mean C = 27.1\n| Nov mean C = 26.2\n| Dec mean C = 24.8\n|year mean C = 26.6\n| Jan low C = 21.3\n| Feb low C = 21.5\n| Mar low C = 22.3\n| Apr low C = 23.3\n| May low C = 23.9\n| Jun low C = 24.4\n| Jul low C = 24.1\n| Aug low C = 24.3\n| Sep low C = 24.0\n| Oct low C = 23.7\n| Nov low C = 22.9\n| Dec low C = 21.9\n|year low C = 23.1\n| Jan record low C = 14.3\n| Feb record low C = 15.3\n| Mar record low C = 17.1\n| Apr record low C = 17.7\n| May record low C = 20.0\n| Jun record low C = 20.0\n| Jul record low C = 20.0\n| Aug record low C = 20.0\n| Sep record low C = 19.6\n| Oct record low C = 18.3\n| Nov record low C = 17.1\n| Dec record low C = 16.1\n|year record low C = 14.3\n|rain colour = green\n| Jan rain mm = 220.2\n| Feb rain mm = 179.1\n| Mar rain mm = 185.0\n| Apr rain mm = 215.4\n| May rain mm = 329.1\n| Jun rain mm = 238.8\n| Jul rain mm = 272.7\n| Aug rain mm = 164.9\n| Sep rain mm = 282.1\n| Oct rain mm = 386.0\n| Nov rain mm = 368.7\n| Dec rain mm = 405.9\n|year rain mm = 3247.9\n|unit rain days = 0.1 mm\n| Jan rain days = 16\n| Feb rain days = 14\n| Mar rain days = 14\n| Apr rain days = 14\n| May rain days = 16\n| Jun rain days = 16\n| Jul rain days = 17\n| Aug rain days = 15\n| Sep rain days = 15\n| Oct rain days = 18\n| Nov rain days = 16\n| Dec rain days = 15\n|year rain days = 186\n| Jan humidity = 86\n| Feb humidity = 86\n| Mar humidity = 85\n| Apr humidity = 85\n| May humidity = 85\n| Jun humidity = 84\n| Jul humidity = 83\n| Aug humidity = 83\n| Sep humidity = 83\n| Oct humidity = 85\n| Nov humidity = 85\n| Dec humidity = 86\n|year humidity = 85\n| source 1 = [[Philippine Atmospheric, Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration|PAGASA]]<ref name=PAGASAnormals>\n{{cite web\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180923155003/https://data.gov.ph/sites/default/files/pagasanormvalbalerquez1995-2010.csv\n| archivedate = 23 September 2018\n| url = https://data.gov.ph/?q=dataset/climatological-normal-values/resource/08eb61cd-7c75-428a-a125-e154617d2b0d\n| title = Baler, Aurora Climatological Normal Values\n| publisher = Philippine Atmospheric, Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration\n| accessdate = 23 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=PAGASAextremes>\n{{cite web\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180923155144/https://data.gov.ph/sites/default/files/pagasaclimextrbaleraur.csv\n| archivedate = 23 September 2018\n| url = https://data.gov.ph/?q=dataset/climatological-extremes/resource/255ae1fd-7e59-46b0-8b67-cf0c7f7694c0\n| title = Baler, Aurora Climatological Extremes\n| publisher = Philippine Atmospheric, Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration\n| accessdate = 23 September 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Demographics==\n\n{{Philippine Census\n| cols = 2\n| align= none\n| title= Population census of Baler\n| 1903 = 2417\n| 1918 = 3413\n| 1939 = 11887\n| 1948 = 17182\n| 1960 = 10350\n| 1970 = 14632\n| 1975 = 16046\n| 1980 = 18349\n| 1990 = 24689\n| 1995 = 26919\n| 2000 = 29923\n| 2007 = 34492\n| 2010 = 36010\n| 2015 = 39562\n| 2020 =\n| 2025 =\n| 2030 =\n| footnote= Source: [[Philippine Statistics Authority]]{{PH census|2015}}{{PH census|2010}}{{PH census|2007}}{{LWUA population data}} \n}}\n\nPeople with connections to the town are referred to as Balerenos. Prior to the arrival of Spanish missionaries in Baler in 1609, settlements by [[Aeta people]] and [[Ilongot]] in Baler's coast and mountain areas already exists. [[Tagalog people|Tagalogs]], some originating from [[Palanan]] and [[Infanta, Quezon]], came in to the area to trade by boat. Some Tagalogs settled in Baler and married with the Aeta and Ilongots.<ref name=Aurorapeople>{{cite web|last1=Mesina|first1=Ilovita|title=Baler And Its People, The Aurorans|url=http://www.aurora.ph/baler-aurora-book/baler-and-its-people.html|website=Aurora.ph|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Spanish brought in Filipino acolytes from other areas of Luzon from 1609 to 1899. During this period, Baler can only be access by sea though the town saw increase migration from other parts of Luzon such as [[Laguna (province)|Laguna]], [[Tayabas]], and [[Bicol Region|Bicol]] from the south. The opening of the Baler-Bongabon Road allowed easier migration of people from [[Ilocos Region|Ilocos]] and [[Isabela (province)|Isabela]] areas from the north. The road also allowed [[Igorot people]] and [[Batangas|Batangue\u00f1os]] to settle in Baler.<ref name=Aurorapeople/>\n\nIn the {{PH wikidata|population_as_of}}, Baler had a population of {{PH wikidata|population_total}}.{{PH census|current}} The population density was {{convert|{{sigfig|{{PH wikidata|population_total}}/{{PH wikidata|area}}|2}}|PD/km2}}.\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Local government==\n[[File:Baler Municipal Hall.jpg|thumb|Baler Municipal Hall]]\nThe Current Officials of Baler, Aurora (as of May 19, 2019)<ref>{{cite web|title=Government Officials of Aurora, Philippines|url=http://www.aurora.ph/officials.html|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Designation\n|-\n| Angara, Rhett Ronan || Mayor\n|-\n| Ong, Bobong || Vice Mayor\n|-\n| Valenzuela, Pandus || Member Sangguniang Bayan\n|-\n| Galban, Manny || Member Sangguniang Bayan\n|-\n| Ong, Danilo || Member Sangguniang Bayan\n|-\n| Guerrero, Santino Rosauro || Member Sangguniang Bayan\n|-\n| Morillo, Eto || Member Sangguniang Bayan\n|-\n| Buluag, Edith || Member Sangguniang Bayan\n|-\n| Zubia, Francisco III || Member Sangguniang Bayan\n|-\n| Villacorte, Ellah || Member Sangguniang Bayan\n|}\n\n==Culture==\nBaler annually observes the [[Philippine\u2013Spanish Friendship Day]] which commemorates the end of the historic [[Siege of Baler]]<ref name=\"rpspain1\">{{cite news|last1=Galvez|first1=Manny|title=RP-Spain Friendship Day marked today in Bale|url=https://beta.philstar.com/nation/2010/07/02/589112/rp-spain-friendship-day-marked-today-baler|accessdate=21 February 2018|work=The Philippine Star|date=2 July 2010}}</ref> and celebrates [[Philippines\u2013Spain relations]] developed since then.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Quismundo|first1=Tarra|title=Filipino, Spanish officials mark Friendship Day in Baler, Aurora|url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/140677/filipino-spanish-officials-mark-friendship-day-in-baler-quezon|accessdate=21 February 2018|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=5 July 2016}}</ref> It is usually held every June 30 and the rites which was first done in the provincial capital has also been observed in other parts of the country as well as parts of Spain.<ref name=\"rpspain1\"/>\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Manuel L. Quezon]], first [[President of the Philippines|President]] of the [[Commonwealth of the Philippines]]\n* [[Aurora Quezon]], former First Lady of the Philippines, wife of Commonwealth President Manuel L. Quezon\n* [[Eunice Pablo Guerrero-Cucueco]], the first female governor of Aurora province\n* Loreto Bihasa, a veteran whose exploits in the [[Korean War]] was made into a movie starring [[Vic Vargas]]\n* [[Edgardo Angara]], former Senate President, former [[University of the Philippines]] president and longest-serving senator in the Philippines.\n* [[Bella Angara]], the first and the only woman in the history of the Philippine Congress to become house majority floor leader\n* [[Sonny Angara]], one of the recipients of the Ten Outstanding Young Men (TOYM) Awards for 2010, who received his trophy from President [[Benigno Aquino III]], former President of the Philippines.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed heights=100px>  <!-- Add additional image only to Commons category:Baler, Aurora  -->\nFile:Baler Public Market in Aurora province.jpg|Baler Public Market\nFile:Sabang2jf.JPG|Outer Banks, Labasin{{nbhyph}}Sabang Beach\nFile:Erm8jf.jpg|View of [[Baler Bay]] from Ermita Hill\nFile:DigisitLukso2jf.jpg|Rocky islets in Diguisit Bay\nFile:Dicasalarin Cove.jpg|Dicasalarin Cove\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Baler}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.batangbaler.net Batang Baler]\n* [http://www.aurora.ph/baler.html Aurora, Philippines \u2013 Baler]\n\n{{Geographic location\n| Centre    = Baler\n| North     = [[Dipaculao, Aurora|Dipaculao]]\n| Northeast = ''[[Baler&nbsp;Bay]]''\n| East      = ''[[Philippine&nbsp;Sea]]''\n| South     = [[San Luis, Aurora|San&nbsp;Luis]]\n| West      = [[Maria Aurora, Aurora|Maria&nbsp;Aurora]]\n}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Articles related to Baler, Aurora\n| state = uncollapsed\n| list  = \n{{Aurora|state=expanded}}\n{{Central Luzon}}\n{{Philippine Provincial Capitals}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Municipalities of Aurora (province)]]\n[[Category:Provincial capitals of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Surfing locations in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1609]]\n", "name_user": "Uzume", "label": "safe", "comment": "defaults to the current QID", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baler,_Aurora"}
{"title_page": "Alf Ramsey", "text_new": "{{pp-vand|small=yes}}\n{{short description|English football player and manager (1920\u20131999)}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = Sir Alf Ramsey\n|image          = Alf Ramsey (1969).jpg\n|image_size     =\n|caption        = Ramsey as [[England national football team manager|England manager]] in November 1969\n|alt            =\n|fullname       = Alfred Ernest Ramsey\n|birth_date     = {{birth date|1920|1|22|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Dagenham]], Essex, England\n|death_date     = {{death date and age|1999|4|28|1920|1|22|df=y}}\n|death_place    = [[Ipswich]], Suffolk, England\n|height         = {{height|ft=5|in=8+1/4}}<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamPlyrsBios/PlayersR/BioRamseyAE.html | publisher = England Football Online | title = Alf Ramsey | accessdate = 20 February 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180702135114/http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamPlyrsBios/PlayersR/BioRamseyAE.html | archive-date = 2 July 2018 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n|position       = [[Right-back]]\n|youthyears1    =\n|youthclubs1    = Five Elms\n|years1         = 1943\u20131949\n|clubs1         = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]\n|caps1          = 90\n|goals1         = 8\n|years2         = 1949\u20131955\n|clubs2         = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]\n|caps2          = 226\n|goals2         = 24\n|totalcaps      = 316\n|totalgoals     = 32\n|nationalyears1 = 1948\n|nationalteam1  = [[England national football B team|England B]]\n|nationalcaps1  = 1\n|nationalgoals1 = 0\n|nationalyears2 = 1948\u20131953\n|nationalteam2  = [[England national football team|England]]\n|nationalcaps2  = 32\n|nationalgoals2 = 3\n|manageryears1  = 1955\u20131963\n|managerclubs1  = [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]\n|manageryears2  = 1963\u20131974\n|managerclubs2  = [[England national football team|England]]\n|manageryears3  = 1977\u20131978\n|managerclubs3  = [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]\n|manageryears4  = 1979\u20131980\n|managerclubs4  = [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]] (Technical director)\n}}\n'''Sir Alfred Ernest Ramsey''' (22 January 1920&nbsp;\u2013 28 April 1999) was an English [[association football|football]] player and [[Manager (association football)|manager]]. As a player, he represented [[England national football team|the England national team]] and captained the side, but he is best known for his time as [[England national football team manager|England manager]] from 1963 to 1974, which included guiding them to victory in the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]]. Knighted in 1967 in recognition of the World Cup win, Ramsey also managed his country to third place in the [[UEFA Euro 1968|1968 European Championship]] and the quarter-finals of the [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970 World Cup]] and the [[UEFA Euro 1972|1972 European Championship]] respectively. As a player, Ramsey was a [[defender (association football)|defender]] and a member of England's [[1950 FIFA World Cup|1950 World Cup]] squad.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Alfred-Ernest-Ramsey|title=Sir Alfred Ernest Ramsey: British soccer player and manager |website=Britannica|date=24 April 2020|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nRamsey was born and raised in a quiet [[Essex]] village. He showed sporting promise from an early age and, after serving in the British Army during the [[World War II|Second World War]], embarked on a football career, primarily as a [[right-back]]. He was considered a rather slow but accomplished player with a tremendous grasp of the tactical side of the game. Nicknamed \"The General\", he played for England 32 times between 1948 and 1953, captaining the side three times, scoring three times and appearing in the 1950 World Cup. He played his club football for [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] and [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and was part of the Tottenham side that won the [[List of English football champions|English League championship]] in the [[1950\u201351 Football League|1950\u201351 season]].<ref>{{Cite news |first=Asif |last=Burhan|url=https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/s/modest-beginnings-sir-alf-ramsey|title=The improbable success of Alf Ramsey|website=morningstaronline|date=22 January 2020|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nRamsey retired from playing aged 35 to become the manager of [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]], then in the [[English football league system|third tier of English football]]. Ipswich rose through the divisions over the next six years, winning the [[Football League Third Division South|Third Division South]] in [[1956\u201357 Football League|1956\u201357]] and the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] in [[1960\u201361 Football League|1960\u201361]]. In the [[1961\u201362 Football League|1961\u201362 season]], Ipswich's first ever campaign in the top division, Ramsey's team defied expectations to become champions of England. Ramsey took charge of the England team a year later. In a distinct break with common practice of the day, he used a narrow formation that led to his England side being dubbed \"The Wingless Wonders\". England's World Cup victory at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]] in 1966 made Ramsey a national hero, though he had his critics, both at the time and since. He lost the England job acrimoniously, following the team's failure to qualify for the [[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974 World Cup]].\n\nAfter managing England, Ramsey briefly held football-related roles at [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] and [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]], before retiring in 1979\u201380. He led a somewhat reclusive life in [[Ipswich]] over the next two decades and died in 1999, aged 79. A statue of Ramsey was dedicated at the reconstructed [[Wembley Stadium]] in 2009, and various honours have been afforded to him in Ipswich. He is the first person to have been inducted into the [[English Football Hall of Fame]] twice: an inaugural inductee in 2002, in recognition of his achievements as a manager and admitted again in 2010 for his achievements as a player. He remains widely regarded as one of British football's all-time great managers.\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n==Early life==\n\n===Dagenham===\n[[File:Dagenham village.jpg|thumb|The village green in [[Dagenham]], Ramsey's birthplace and childhood home (2007)]]\nAlfred Ernest Ramsey was born on 22 January 1920 at 6 Parrish Cottages, Halbutt Street in [[Dagenham]], which was then an [[agriculture|agrarian]] village in Essex, about {{convert|10|mi}} east of central London.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=1\u20138}} He was the third of five children, four boys and a girl, born to Herbert Ramsey, a manual labourer who worked a [[smallholding]], kept pigs and drove a horse-drawn [[dustcart]], and his wife Florence (''n\u00e9e'' Bixby). Parrish Cottages lacked hot running water and electricity, and the only toilet was outside. Such conditions were typical of Dagenham during this period, although Ramsey's street gradually became something of an anachronism as he grew up. From 1921, [[London County Council]] transformed the area into the [[Becontree]] estate, a vast urban community that by 1934 was home to 120,000 people and the [[Ford Dagenham]] automobile factory. Parrish Cottages remained largely untouched: electricity was not installed until the 1950s, and even then only with the reluctant approval of Ramsey's mother, who, according to a neighbour, was frightened of it.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=1\u20138}} In the recollection of a childhood contemporary, Phil Cairns, the Ramsey house was \"little more than a wooden hut\".{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=1\u20138}}\n\nThe young Alf Ramsey was described by his friend Fred Tibble as \"a very quiet boy who really loved sport\".{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=1\u20138}} In his 1952 autobiography ''Talking Football'', Ramsey described \"liv[ing] for the open air from the moment I could toddle\",{{sfn|Ramsey|1952|p=12}} spending hours each day in the meadow behind the family cottage, playing ball games with his brothers. He learned skills such as ball control, kicking and heading with a [[tennis ball]].{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=1\u20138}} From the age of five, Ramsey attended Becontree Heath School, which had a roll of about 200 pupils aged from four to fourteen. He and his brothers had to walk two hours from their house to get there, and passed a ball between each other on the way to break the monotony. Ramsey was not especially popular socially, nor particularly diligent as a student, but he excelled in sports. In addition to football, he played [[cricket]] to a high standard and represented the school in the [[high jump]], the [[long jump]], and both the [[100-yard dash|100-yard]] and 200-yard dash. Despite his diminutive stature, he also enjoyed [[boxing]] until an incident when he was 10 years old, when a much larger opponent\u2014\"as wide as I was tall\" in Ramsey's recollection\u2014gave him a severe beating in a school tournament.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=1\u20138}} Ramsey carried a noticeable scar above his mouth, a memento of this fight, for the rest of his life.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=1\u20138}}\n\n\"He was very withdrawn, almost surly\", Cairns recalled, \"but he became animated on the football field\".{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=1\u20138}} Ramsey was selected to play for Becontree Heath School when he was only seven years old, playing at [[Inside forward|inside-left]] alongside boys as old as fourteen; his nine-year-old brother Len was at inside-right. Alf's selection for the school team prompted the purchase of his first pair of football boots. Two years later, aged nine, he became captain of the school team. By this point he had switched to playing at [[Defender (association football)|centre-half]]\u2014the key position of the [[WM formation|\"WM\" formation]] then favoured in British football, between the full-backs and the forwards.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=1\u20138}} His main strength was generally perceived to be his extremely accurate passing; his chief shortcoming was a lack of pace, for which Ramsey compensated by learning to read the game and position himself well.{{sfn|Bowler|1999|pp=21\u201325}} Ramsey played for teams representing the schools of Dagenham and Essex County respectively, and trialled unsuccessfully for the London schools team while at Becontree.{{sfn|Bowler|1999|pp=21\u201325}} While he was at school, his brother Albert took him to see his first [[English Football League|Football League]] match, watching their favourite team, [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], play against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].{{sfn|Ramsey|1952|p=14}} This was the only senior match Alf would attend before playing in them himself.{{sfn|Bowler|1999|pp=26\u201328}} He later wrote that his main recollection of it was the performance of one of the Arsenal forwards, the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] international [[Alex James (footballer)|Alex James]].{{sfn|Ramsey|1952|p=14}}\n\nOn leaving school in 1934, the 14-year-old Ramsey tried to get a job at the Ford plant, then told his family he intended to become a [[greengrocer]]. To that end he became an apprentice at a local branch of the [[Co-op Food|Co-op]], delivering groceries on a bicycle. The manual work helped to bulk up Ramsey's physique,{{sfn|Bowler|1999|pp=25\u201326}} but he found himself unable to play organised football because he had to work on Saturday afternoons. After a two-year hiatus, he returned to the game when he joined Five Elms, a newly formed amateur club whose matches on Thursdays fitted with his work schedule.{{sfn|Ramsey|1952|p=14}} About a year later, during the 1937\u201338 season, Ramsey was spotted by [[Ned Liddell]], a [[Scout (association football)|scout]] from [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]],{{sfn|Bowler|1999|pp=28\u201330}} then a well-established top-flight club.<ref name=\"rssf\">{{cite web|title=English Clubs Divisional Movements 1888\u20132005|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engall.html|publisher=[[RSSSF]]|accessdate=2 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160805092856/http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engall.html|archive-date=5 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Liddell offered a contract as an amateur. Rather than signing on the spot, Ramsey asked to take the forms home to examine first; he signed them that night and sent them to Portsmouth by post.{{sfn|Ramsey|1952|p=15}} Much to Ramsey's disappointment, Portsmouth did not contact him again. He spent the next two years working at the Co-op while playing cricket in the summer and football in the winter.{{sfn|Bowler|1999|pp=29\u201330}}{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|p=27}}\n\n===Second World War===\n\n====Military service====\n[[File:The British Army in the United Kingdom 1939-45 H4953A.jpg|thumb|A [[Universal Carrier]] Mk I of Ramsey's regiment, with [[Bren light machine gun|Bren gun]] mounted for [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft]] use (1940)|alt=An open-topped military vehicle containing soldiers, who point a mortar and a machine gun upwards.]]\nAfter the outbreak of the [[World War II|Second World War]] in 1939, Ramsey was conscripted into the [[British Army]] on 24 June 1940.{{sfn|Ramsey|1952|p=16}} He was assigned to the [[Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry]] and underwent his initial training in [[Truro]], where he and other recruits were housed in a hotel commandeered by the army. Ramsey found the experience a thrilling adventure.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|p=28}} \"Until I travelled to [[Cornwall]], the longest journey I had undertaken was a trip to [[Brighton]] by train\", he recalled. \"It was the first time I had ever been into a hotel! Even with us sleeping twelve to a room, on straw mattresses, could not end for me the awe of living in a swagger hotel.\"{{sfn|Ramsey|1952|p=17}} \"That set the tone for Alf's war\", [[Leo McKinstry]] suggests in his 2010 biography; attached to his regiment's 6th Battalion, Ramsey spent the entire war in Britain on home defence duties.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=28\u201329}} The training was still physically demanding though, and, in Ramsey's words, made him \"a fitter young fellow than when I reported for duty as a grocery apprentice from Dagenham.\"{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=28\u201329}}\n\nWriting in 1952, Ramsey would call joining the army \"one of the greatest things which ever happened to me\", adding \"I learnt, in a few weeks, more about life in general that I had picked up in years at home.\"{{sfn|Ramsey|1952|p=17}} Military life taught Ramsey about discipline and leadership, and improved his social skills: \"I have never been very good at mixing with people but you have to in the army or else you are in trouble\", the journalist Nigel Clarke recalled him saying.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=28\u201329}} Ramsey rose to be a [[company quartermaster sergeant]] in an [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft]] unit.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=28\u201329}}\n\n====Wartime football====\nMilitary service also allowed Ramsey to play football more regularly, and at a higher standard than before.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=30\u201331}} In late 1940 he was posted to [[St Austell]], on the south coast of Cornwall, where he manned beach defences and became captain of the battalion football team, playing at centre-half or [[centre-forward]] as circumstances dictated. After three years in various seaside postings, Ramsey was, in 1943, moved to [[Barton Stacey]] in [[Hampshire]], where he came under the command of a Colonel Fletcher, himself an accomplished footballer. Ramsey's battalion team by this time featured players from a number of Football League clubs, including the [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] forward [[Len Townsend]] and Arsenal's [[Cyril Hodges]].{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=30\u201331}} Ramsey played at centre-half for his battalion team as [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] defeated them 10\u20133 at [[The Dell, Southampton|the Dell]] in a pre-season [[Exhibition game|friendly]] on 21 August 1943, and a week later played again as the battalion took on Southampton's [[reserve team]]. The soldiers won the second match 4\u20131.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=30\u201331}}\n\n[[File:Oak Road End at Kenilworth Road, 1980.jpg|thumb|left|[[Kenilworth Road]], [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]]'s ground, where Ramsey first played for [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in the wartime [[Football League North and South|Football League South]] (1980)|alt=A football match in progress at a modest, traditional British football ground.]]\nOn 8 October 1943, Colonel Fletcher called Ramsey to his office to inform him that Southampton needed a centre-half for their [[Glossary of association football terms#F|first-team]] match [[Road (sports)|away]] to [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] the next day, and had enquired about the sergeant's availability. The 23-year-old Ramsey was cautious, saying he lacked experience, but said he would \"give it a try\" when the colonel suggested that playing might set him on the way to a [[Professionalism in association football|professional football career]].{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=30\u201331}} The next day, while en route to [[Luton]] by train, Ramsey signed for Southampton as an amateur,{{sfn|Chalk|Holley|Bull|2013|pp=440\u2013441}} making his debut for the club at Luton's [[Kenilworth Road]] ground. Ramsey gave away a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]] late in the game with Southampton 2\u20131 ahead, allowing Luton to equalise, but Southampton managed to win 3\u20132.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=33\u201334}} He played in three more matches for the team during the 1943\u201344 season before his battalion's posting to [[County Durham]] forced his absence. After his unit returned to the south coast at the start of the 1944\u201345 season, Ramsey played in a trial match at Southampton, and performed well enough that the club offered a professional contract on wages of \u00a32 per match. Ramsey was still uncertain about pursuing a football career; he signed the contract only after Southampton assured him that he could leave at the end of the season if he wished.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=33\u201334}}\n\nRamsey was injured during the 1944\u201345 pre-season, ironically while playing against Southampton for his battalion team, so he did not make his first appearance as a professional until December. During the match, against Arsenal at [[White Hart Lane]],{{#tag:ref|Arsenal played at White Hart Lane during the war because [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]] was bombed in [[the Blitz]].{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=34\u201335}}|group=\"n\"|name=\"highburybombed\"}} Ramsey played centre-half opposite the formidable Arsenal centre-forward [[Ted Drake]] and according to McKinstry \"had the best game of his career to date.\"{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=34\u201335}} Drake scored twice, but Ramsey still felt that he had proven his ability to play league football.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=34\u201335}} On 3 March 1945, against Luton Town at the Dell, Ramsey was switched to inside-left because of injuries elsewhere in the team; he scored four goals in a 12\u20133 Southampton win.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=34\u201335}}{{sfn|Chalk|Holley|1987|p=108}} The ''[[Southern Daily Echo]]'' reported \"he can certainly hammer a ball.\"{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=34\u201335}} Ramsey finished the season having made 11 [[Football League North and South|League South]] appearances.{{sfn|Chalk|Holley|1987|p=108}}\n\nRamsey remained in the army during [[1945\u201346 in English football|1945\u201346, the first football season after the war]]. Starting as a centre-forward, he scored two goals in each of Southampton's opening two games, then a [[Hat-trick (association football)|hat-trick]] in a 6\u20132 victory at [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] on 6 October 1945.{{sfn|Chalk|Holley|1987|p=109}} He played in 13 League South matches before military commitments again intervened\u2014in December 1945 he was deployed to [[Mandatory Palestine]], where he accepted an invitation to captain a football team representing the British garrison. This side included [[Arthur Rowley]], who later scored hundreds of goals for [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] and [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]], and the future Scotland international forward [[Jimmy Mason (footballer, born 1919)|Jimmy Mason]].{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=35\u201336}} Ramsey returned to England in June 1946 to find himself entertaining overtures from both the new Southampton manager [[Bill Dodgin Sr.|Bill Dodgin]] and the Dagenham Co-op, the latter of which offered Ramsey his pre-war job back. Ramsey initially turned Southampton down, but accepted after the club offered better terms: \u00a36 per week during the summer, \u00a37 in winter and \u00a38 if he was selected for the league team. He was formally [[Military discharge|discharged]] from the army soon after.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=36\u201338}}\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Southampton===\n\nThe regular Football League restarted in time for the [[1946\u201347 Football League|1946\u201347 season]]. Ramsey moved into club-owned lodgings in Southampton with a close friend from the army, [[Alf Freeman (footballer, born 1920)|Alf Freeman]], an inside-forward who had also signed for the club.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=47\u201348}} Ramsey started the season in the reserve team, selected at centre-forward, and scored in each of the first three games.{{sfn|Holley|Chalk|2003|p=432}} After five matches, Dodgin and the club trainer [[Sydney Cann]] made a decision that changed the course of Ramsey's professional playing career: deciding that neither centre-half nor centre-forward truly suited him, they moved him to [[right-back]]. McKinstry calls this \"exactly the right place for Alf\", citing Ramsey's tactical knowledge and fine passing.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|p=38}} A close master-and-pupil relationship developed between Ramsey and Cann, who had played at full-back for [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]], [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]]. During training sessions, the two had long discussions about tactics and individual techniques. {{nobreak|\"[Alf]}} wanted to learn about the game from top to bottom\", Cann recalled; \"I have never known anyone with the same quickness of learning as Alf Ramsey. He would never accept anything on its face value&nbsp;... He was the type of player who was a manager's dream because you could talk about a decision and he would accept it and there it was, in his game.\"{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=39\u201340}}\n\nRamsey made his full league debut on 26 October 1946, in a [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] match against [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] at the Dell, replacing the injured regular right-back [[Bill Ellerington]].{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=39\u201340}} The nervous Ramsey was helped through the match by the calm reassurance and guidance of the experienced Southampton captain [[Bill Rochford]], the team's other full-back.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=40\u201341}} Southampton won 5\u20131, their joint-biggest win of the 1946\u201347 season,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.11v11.com/teams/southampton/tab/matches/season/1947/ | title=Southampton: 1946\u201347 season | work=www.11v11.com | publisher=Association of Football Statisticians | location=London | accessdate=18 February 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160319182121/http://www.11v11.com/teams/southampton/tab/matches/season/1947/ | archive-date=19 March 2016 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Saintsdebut\">{{cite web | url=http://www.11v11.com/matches/southampton-v-plymouth-argyle-26-october-1946-103789/ | title=Southampton v Plymouth Argyle, 26 October 1946 | work=www.11v11.com | publisher=Association of Football Statisticians | location=London | accessdate=25 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925112740/http://www.11v11.com/matches/southampton-v-plymouth-argyle-26-october-1946-103789/ | archive-date=25 September 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> but Ramsey found the pace of the regular peacetime Football League a drastic step up. \"Their reactions to moves were so speedy they had completed a pass, for instance, when I was still thinking things over\", he later wrote.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=40\u201341}} After one more game, Ellerington was reinstated and Ramsey went back to the reserves.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=40\u201341}} Ramsey was kept out of the first team until January 1947, when Ellerington was injured again shortly before an away match against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]. Southampton lost 3\u20131, but Ramsey was generally considered to have acquitted himself well. He kept his place for the rest of the season, gradually growing in confidence. Dodgin praised Ramsey in a February 1947 interview as a \"player who thinks football, talks football and lives football\".{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=42\u201343}}\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = He had a very, very good football brain. If he hadn't, he would not have played where he did, because he was not the most nimble of players. Not particularly brilliant in the air, because he did not have the stature to jump up. But he was a decent tackler and a great passer. He could read the game so well, that was his big asset. That was why he became such a great manager.\n |source = [[Eric Day]], one of Ramsey's Southampton teammates{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|p=44}}\n |quoted = 1\n |width = 33%\n}}\nA formative experience for Ramsey during his first peacetime season was playing for Southampton against Manchester City in April 1947. Playing at full-back for City was the 38-year-old [[Sam Barkas]], a former England international near the end of his last season. Ramsey was greatly impressed by Barkas's positional sense and accurate passing, and adopted him as a role model.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=42\u201343}} The following season, [[1947\u201348 Football League|1947\u201348]], Ramsey firmly established himself ahead of Ellerington in the Southampton team, and was the only player at the club to appear in all 42 League matches.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=45\u201346}}\n\nThe consensus on Ramsey's playing style among his fellow professionals was that he was rather slow, but possessed an excellent positional sense, read the game better than most, and distributed the ball exceptionally well for a defender.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=44\u201345, 54}}<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1524736/Jimmy-Leadbetter.html | newspaper = The Daily Telegraph | title = Jimmy Leadbetter | date = 25 July 2006 | accessdate = 22 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150925095517/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1524736/Jimmy-Leadbetter.html | archive-date = 25 September 2015 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Taking after his Southampton captain Bill Rochford, he preferred to play the ball out of defence rather than simply [[Glossary of association football terms#C|clearing]] it as quickly as possible.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|p=41}}<ref>{{Cite news | title = He shows up 'clear at any price' backs | work = [[Gloucester Citizen]]| date = 24 October 1950 | page = 11 | url = http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000325/19501024/072/0011 | via = [[British Newspaper Archive]] | accessdate = 2 September 2015}}</ref> He became a specialist penalty taker due to his coolness and ability to anticipate the [[goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]].<ref>{{Cite news | title = Alf. Ramsey is present no. 1 penalty expert | page = 7 | work = [[Sunderland Echo]] | date = 15 December 1951 | via = [[British Newspaper Archive]] | accessdate = 2 September 2015| url = http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000687/19510925/030/0002}}</ref> [[Ted Bates (footballer)|Ted Bates]], one of Ramsey's Southampton teammates, described him as \"lacking both height and speed\", but credited him with a \"razor-sharp brain&nbsp;... he would never get into a situation that exposed him.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/1999/may/01/newsstory.sport23 | title=A man with no equal | work=The Guardian | date=1 May 1999 | accessdate=27 August 2015 | last=Langley | first=Mike | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908030122/http://www.theguardian.com/football/1999/may/01/newsstory.sport23 | archive-date=8 September 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSouthampton failed to win promotion during the 1947\u201348 season, finishing third behind Birmingham City and Newcastle United, but it was still a successful campaign for them and by its end Ramsey had become one of the club's main players,{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=55\u201357}} taking on the captain's role on occasion.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|p=62}} In May 1948 he was selected as part of a 16-man England squad to tour Switzerland and Italy; the flight to [[Geneva]] was his first time in an aeroplane.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=55\u201357}} On his return from international duty he flew to [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] to join the rest of the Southampton team on a club tour of Brazil. Southampton had lost every game in Brazil so far, and spirits were low.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=58\u201361}} Ramsey restored morale and contributed to a new plan to counter the Brazilian tactics, which were much more fluid than those favoured by English teams of the time. Ramsey suggested that Southampton could use long diagonal passes to exploit the gaps the Brazilian defenders left behind them as they ran upfield to attack. McKinstry notes the similarity of this thinking to some of the tactics Ramsey later used as manager of [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]].{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=58\u201361}} Southampton beat [[Sport Club Corinthians Paulista|Corinthians]] 2\u20131 in their next game before ending the tour with a draw and a defeat.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=58\u201361}} Ramsey was impressed by the South Americans' footballing ability, but not by the conduct of their players, pressmen, administrators or fans; McKinstry considers the experience to have \"fed Alf's nascent [[xenophobia]]\".{{#tag:ref|A riot threatened to break out during the match against Corinthians after one of the home players was sent off. Ramsey wrote in 1952: \"Our officials were treated very badly by some spectators, and just when I thought things had quietened down, some wild-eyed negroes climbed over the wire fencing surrounding the pitch and things again looked dangerous&nbsp;... Outside our dressing-room they demonstrated\u2014because we had won!\u2014for over an hour.\"{{sfn|Ramsey|1952|pp=41\u201342}}|group=\"n\"|name=\"nascentxenophobia\"}}\n\nBy the middle of the [[1948\u201349 Football League|1948\u201349 season]] Ramsey had made his first appearance for the England national team and made a total of 90 league and 6 [[FA Cup]] appearances for Southampton, scoring eight goals.<ref name=\"11v11stats\">{{cite web | url=http://www.11v11.com/players/alf-ramsey-27133/ | title=Alf Ramsey | work=www.11v11.com | publisher=Association of Football Statisticians | location=London | accessdate=25 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925112819/http://www.11v11.com/players/alf-ramsey-27133/ | archive-date=25 September 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> He made what turned out to be his final competitive appearance for Southampton on 8 January 1949, in a 2\u20131 away defeat to [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.11v11.com/matches/sheffield-wednesday-v-southampton-08-january-1949-209730/ | title=Sheffield Wednesday v Southampton, 08 January 1949 | work=www.11v11.com | publisher=Association of Football Statisticians | location=London | accessdate=25 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926150157/http://www.11v11.com/matches/sheffield-wednesday-v-southampton-08-january-1949-209730/ | archive-date=26 September 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nIn a friendly away at Plymouth Argyle a week later, he slipped as he went into a tackle and injured his knee. Dodgin brought Bill Ellerington back into the side to replace Ramsey while he recovered, and Ellerington performed strongly as Southampton won eight and drew two of the next 10 matches.{{sfn|Bowler|1999|p=54}} Dodgin told Ramsey that, given Ellerington's good form, Ramsey was \"going to find it very hard\" to regain his place in the team.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|p=65}} Ramsey, not yet in his 30s, was infuriated and considered this a direct insult by Dodgin:{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=65\u201370}} he subsequently asked Southampton to place him on the [[transfer market|transfer list]] on 7 March 1949.<ref name=SFCtransfer>{{cite news |title=Untitled |work=Aberdeen Journal |date=9 March 1949 |accessdate=26 August 2015 |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000578/19490309/064/0004| via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> He obsessed about Dodgin's comment. \"The world did indeed appear a dark and unfriendly place\", he later said; \"...&nbsp;for one fleeting moment I seriously contemplated quitting football.\"{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=65\u201370}}\n\nRamsey's opinion that Dodgin had treated him unfairly was not shared by the other Southampton players, who respected Ellerington as a player of comparable ability.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=65\u201370}} According to the [[Wing half|wing-half]] [[Joe Mallett]], Ramsey was also motivated to leave by a dressing-room row with his captain Bill Rochford at half-time during that final league match against Sheffield Wednesday: one of the Sheffield Wednesday goals was blamed on Ramsey's failure to play an opposing winger [[Offside (association football)|offside]].{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=65\u201370}} The Southampton chairman and board tried to persuade Ramsey to stay, but his mind was made up\u2014he told them that if he played in the reserve team it would hinder his chances of playing internationally.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=65\u201370}} [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], Luton Town and [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] were among the clubs who expressed interest in buying him but by the time of the transfer deadline on 16 March only Sheffield Wednesday had made an official bid. [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] came in with a last-minute offer, but there was no time for the transfer to go through, and Ramsey was forced to stay at Southampton for the rest of the season.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=65\u201370}}  On 15 May 1949 the new Tottenham manager [[Arthur Rowe]] revived the offer, and signed Ramsey in a part-exchange deal for \u00a34,500 and [[Wales national football team|Wales]] international winger [[Ernie Jones (footballer, born 1920)|Ernie Jones]]\u2014the transfer was widely reported as being worth \u00a321,000,{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=65\u201370}} then a record for Tottenham.{{#tag:ref|Southampton accepted Jones in lieu of \u00a316,500, making the transfer worth \u00a321,000 in theory. This also set a record for the highest fee ever paid for a full-back.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=65\u201370}}|group=\"n\"|name=\"spursfee\"}}\n\n===Tottenham Hotspur===\n\n====Push-and-run; champions of England====\nA good relationship quickly developed between Ramsey and his new manager, who found that they shared similar personalities and views on tactics. Like Ramsey, Rowe believed in a progressive, fast-moving style of play.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=79\u201383}} These ideas evolved into \"[[Push and run|push-and-run]]\", a playing style unlike anything previously attempted in British football, based around quick passing. Tottenham pioneered the style to good effect\u2014a Spurs player moving forward would lay the ball off to a teammate, then run past the opposing defender to receive an immediate return pass.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=79\u201383}} \"Under Rowe, Alf became far more than a defender\", comments McKinstry.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=79\u201383}} Rowe tasked him with instigating attacks and based much of the Tottenham game plan around Ramsey's accurate passing.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=79\u201383}}\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = Tottenham became a great side through push-and-run, which was tailor-made for Alf. There was no long ball from him, and he was one of the crucial members of the side&nbsp;... Alf played a tremendous part in setting the pass pattern, which wasn't typical of the British game. It was a revolutionary side, very well-knit.\n |source = [[George Robb]], who joined Tottenham in 1951{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|p=96}}\n |quoted = 1\n |width = 33%\n |align = left\n}}\nTottenham started the [[1949\u201350 Football League|1949\u201350 season]] strongly and soon topped the Second Division: between August 1949 and January 1950 they did not lose in 22 matches.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=83\u201385}} Ramsey was an essential part of the team,<ref name=THFCpenpicture>{{cite news |title=Player In The Picture |work=Yorkshire Post and Leeds Intelligencer |date=10 November 1951 |accessdate=25 August 2015 |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000687/19511110/263/0007| via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> having made the right-back position his own; he built effective partnerships with several players, including the wing-half [[Bill Nicholson (footballer)|Bill Nicholson]],<ref name=THFCpenpicture/> the goalkeeper [[Ted Ditchburn]] and the inside-right [[Sonny Walters]].{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=83\u201385}} Ramsey greatly appreciated the licence Rowe gave him to move forward and attack and, in November 1949, in an away match against [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]], he scored what is generally considered the best goal of his career.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=86\u201388}} Shortly after half-time, he intercepted a long pass near the half-way line and, after running 40 yards and dribbling past three Grimsby defenders, smashed the ball past the advancing goalkeeper. The reporter for ''The Enfield Gazette'' wrote that the goal would \"never be forgotten by those privileged to be present\".{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=86\u201388}} Tottenham went on to win the match 3\u20132.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=86\u201388}}\n\nSpurs won the 1949\u201350 Second Division title with seven games to spare, scoring more goals and conceding fewer than any of their rivals, and were [[promotion and relegation|promoted]] to the First Division for the following season.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=86\u201388}} In August 1950, shortly before Tottenham embarked on their first top-flight season since they had been [[promotion and relegation|relegated]] at the end of the [[1934\u201335 Football League|1934\u201335]] campaign, Rowe told the club's annual meeting: \"As much as anything else, I would rate our good time last year to the acquisition of Alf Ramsey.\"{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=86\u201388}} After an uncertain start to the [[1950\u201351 Football League|1950\u201351]] season, Spurs quickly recovered their form of the previous year and by Christmas were top of the table.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=95\u201397}} Ramsey continued to play a key role, according to McKinstry playing \"the best football of his life\": \"He was the master of strategy, the lynchpin of a side that built its attacks from the back, the scheming practitioner who put Rowe's plans into action.\"{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=95\u201397}} Ramsey's understanding of the game and authority on and off the field led to his teammates nicknaming him \"The General\".{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=95\u201397}} On 28 April 1951, with a 1\u20130 home victory over Sheffield Wednesday, Tottenham were crowned [[list of English football champions|champions of England]] only a year after promotion.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=95\u201397}} \"I think fortune shone upon me very handsomely during the 1950\u201351 season\", Ramsey remarked in ''Talking Football''\u2014\"After all, I was a member of one of the finest club teams in years\".{{sfn|Ramsey|1952|p=77}}\n\n====Semi-final error; club captain====\n\nSpurs followed their title win with a second-place finish in the [[1951\u201352 Football League|1951\u201352 season]], but then went into a sharp decline, finishing 10th in [[1952\u201353 Football League|1952\u201353]] and 16th in [[1953\u201354 Football League|1953\u201354]]. The slump was partly because the players who had formed the spine of the championship-winning side were losing their fitness\u2014push-and-run required players of exceptional physical condition, and Ramsey, [[Ron Burgess (footballer)|Ron Burgess]], Nicholson, and others were all past 30.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=128\u2013129}} Ramsey was furthermore affected by a recurring abdominal injury.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=128\u2013129}} His preference for ball play rather than simply clearing it became unpopular among sections of Tottenham's support.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=128\u2013129}} A particularly low ebb came in the [[1952\u201353 FA Cup]] semi-final, against [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] at [[Villa Park]] on 21 March 1953. Ramsey had played well, keeping the Blackpool left-winger [[Bill Perry (footballer)|Bill Perry]] quiet, and with only a minute to spare the game was finely balanced at 1\u20131.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=130\u2013132}} Ramsey then made a fatal error. Having easily beaten Perry to a cross-field pass from a free-kick, he set himself to slide the ball back to the goalkeeper Ditchburn in a situation when most defenders would have cleared it. The ball bounced off Ramsey's knee and ran away from him, allowing Blackpool forward [[Jackie Mudie]] to score. Blackpool won 2\u20131, and went on to win what is commonly referred to as the \"[[1953 FA Cup Final|Matthews Final]]\".{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=130\u2013132}}{{sfn|Bowler|1999|pp=90\u201392}}\n\n[[File:Bill Nicholson (1961).jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Bill Nicholson (footballer)|Bill Nicholson]], with whom Ramsey made an effective partnership when playing at [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], but who was also a rival of his. Both went on to manage top-flight clubs. (1961)]]\nRamsey was vilified by the fans and press after the semi-final, with one Spurs director saying: \"Ramsey stupidly gave the goal away. He could have easily kicked the ball out of play.\"{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=130\u2013132}} Ramsey was publicly contrite\u2014\"I can only say I am terribly sorry\", he told the ''[[Daily Express]]''\u2014but in the Tottenham dressing room he analysed the move that had led to Mudie's goal and attempted to identify others as being at fault.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=130\u2013132}} This notwithstanding, \"for all his reluctance to accept the blame in front of his colleagues, Alf knew he had made a terrible error\", McKinstry writes. The error haunted him profoundly.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=130\u2013132}}{{#tag:ref|The journalist Tony Garnett recalled an occasion at Villa Park some years later when Ramsey, visiting the ground as manager of Ipswich Town, led him to a certain spot on the pitch and said: \"You know, that's where I lost the ball in the FA Cup semi-final and gave away the goal which led us to lose.\"{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=130\u2013132}}|group=\"n\"|name=\"villapark\"}} It began to be speculated during the 1953\u201354 season that he might return to Southampton, who had been relegated to the [[Football League Third Division South|Third Division South]], in a role combining playing duties with coaching. He was not yet finished as a Spurs player, though; indeed in 1954, after Burgess left to join [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea Town]], he was appointed club captain.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=132\u2013133}}\n\nDespite their successful collaboration on the pitch, a strong personal rivalry developed between Ramsey and Nicholson, partly because both liked the idea of staying on at Tottenham in a coaching role after retiring. Rowe made clear to Ramsey that he wanted him to do so, but unfortunately for him Rowe stepped down in February 1955, citing health issues.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=139\u2013141}} Another challenge to Ramsey's position at Tottenham came in the form of [[Danny Blanchflower]], a [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] international wing-half signed from [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] to replace Nicholson. Blanchflower was a more attacking player than Nicholson and thus did not provide the necessary cover for Ramsey to advance upfield; Ramsey also resented the idea that Blanchflower might supplant him as Tottenham's main strategist.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=139\u2013141}}\n\nRowe's illness and Blanchflower's arrival together signalled the end of Ramsey's playing career. Ramsey missed matches during the [[1954\u201355 Football League|1954\u201355 season]] through injury, and in April 1955 suffered what he called \"a terrible roasting\" at the hands of the Leicester City winger [[Derek Hogg]].{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|p=142}} After Tottenham ended the season in 16th place, Rowe retired permanently; his deputy [[Jimmy Anderson (football manager)|Jimmy Anderson]] took over and appointed Nicholson to his coaching staff.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|p=142}} When Ramsey was omitted from a post-season tour of Hungary, despite still being club captain, he realised that his time at Tottenham had come to an end.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|p=142}} He had played a total of 250 competitive games for Tottenham in all competitions, across six seasons.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/dream-teams-tottenham-hotspur-1725589.html?action=gallery&ino=3 | title=Dream Teams: Tottenham Hotspur | work=The Independent | accessdate=7 September 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151002223729/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/dream-teams-tottenham-hotspur-1725589.html?action=gallery&ino=3 | archive-date=2 October 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> \"I was 35 years old and obviously concerned about my future\", he later wrote. \"I really didn't know what was going to happen to me. I knew my days as a player were numbered, and there was only one way things could go for me in this respect\u2014downhill.\"{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|p=142}}\n\n===England international===\nRamsey's first taste of playing as an international had come while he was at Southampton, when he played for [[England national football B team|England B]] against Switzerland B in May 1948.<ref name=11v11international>{{cite web | url=http://www.11v11.com/players/alf-ramsey-27133/ | title=Alf Ramsey | work=www.11v11.com | publisher=Association of Football Statisticians | location=London | accessdate=29 May 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010141943/http://www.11v11.com/players/alf-ramsey-27133/ | archive-date=10 October 2016 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> He made his full England debut in December that year, in a 6\u20130 win over [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] at [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]].<ref name=11v11international/><ref name=glanville/> He briefly lost his England place to his Southampton teammate Bill Ellerington, but following strong performances for Tottenham he returned in England's 2\u20130 home win over [[Italy national football team|Italy]] on 30 November 1949.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|p=99}} Ramsey's introduction to the England set-up coincided with the team's first ever [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] campaign, the British [[Home Nations]] having rejoined football's world governing body [[FIFA]] in 1946 after two decades' absence, therefore being excluded from the first three World Cup tournaments in the 1930s.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=101\u2013107}} [[The Football Association]] (FA) in London had moved on little since the modern game's genesis in the late 19th century, yet remained convinced that English football and the England team were the finest in the world\u2014so superior, indeed, that entering the World Cup was hardly necessary.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=101\u2013107}} The evidence presented for this was that England had never lost at home to any team from outside the British Isles.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=101\u2013107}} The team was picked by a panel of eight FA selectors, with the role of [[England national football team manager|England manager]], held by [[Walter Winterbottom]], combined with that of FA director of coaching.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=101\u2013107}}\n\nEngland's selection of Ramsey and three of his Tottenham teammates\u2014Ditchburn, Nicholson and forward [[Eddie Baily]]\u2014for the [[1950 FIFA World Cup|1950 World Cup]] in Brazil made them the first Tottenham players ever at a World Cup.<ref name=\"SpursWC\">{{cite web | url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/spurs-at-the-world-cup-alf-wales-trio-030614/ | title=Spurs at the World Cup Alf Wales trio | publisher=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. | date=3 June 2014 | accessdate=8 September 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151002042059/http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/spurs-at-the-world-cup-alf-wales-trio-030614/ | archive-date=2 October 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> England were among the favourites to win the tournament, largely because of their reputation.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=108\u2013110}} The team had little preparation, arriving in Brazil only a week before their first game. Ramsey found the South American conditions difficult, noting that \"at the conclusion of even an easy kick-around, I felt infinitely more tired than after a hectic league match at home.\"{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=108\u2013110}} Despite this, an England team including Ramsey won their opening match in [[Rio de Janeiro]], against [[Chile national football team|Chile]], 2\u20130.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=108\u2013110}}\n\n[[File:Billy Wright (1961).jpg|upright|thumb|England captain [[Billy Wright (footballer, born 1924)|Billy Wright]], for whom Ramsey deputised on three occasions (1961)]]\nEngland's next match pitted them against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]]\u2014an opponent they were expected to easily overcome\u2014at the [[Est\u00e1dio Independ\u00eancia]] in [[Belo Horizonte]], {{convert|300|miles}} inland. The selectors again picked Ramsey, but left star winger [[Stanley Matthews]] out on the grounds that England could beat the Americans without him, ignoring Winterbottom's protests.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=110\u2013112}} England dominated the first half. \"I'm not making excuses when I say that in the first 45 minutes we had a year's bad luck\", Ramsey wrote in 1952. \"Shots which appeared certain to score missed by the width of a coat of paint. The American goalkeeper, much to his astonishment, found himself stopping the ball with his body, and on occasions his face, without really knowing what it was all about.\"{{sfn|Ramsey|1952|pp=71\u201372}} The US grabbed a shock lead on 37 minutes when a long shot towards England's penalty area flew into the net off the head of American forward [[Joe Gaetjens]].{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=110\u2013112}}\n\nThe score remained 1\u20130 at half-time, and it was the same story in the second half: England missed a multitude of easy chances, hit the [[Goal post|woodwork]] numerous times and had one effort that appeared to cross the line not given. The England captain [[Billy Wright (footballer, born 1924)|Billy Wright]] recalled that \"even Alf Ramsey, who used to be expressionless throughout a game, threw up his arms and looked to the sky when a perfect free-kick was somehow saved by their unorthodox keeper\".{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=110\u2013112}} No England goal came\u2014the United States [[United States v England (1950 FIFA World Cup)|won 1\u20130]] in what entered English football history as the national team's most embarrassing upset.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=112\u2013114}} Ramsey, who was fiercely patriotic, took the result as an acute personal humiliation. One journalist recalled that on hearing the match mentioned years later, \"his face creased and he looked like a man who had been jabbed in an unhealed wound\".{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=112\u2013114}} England could remain in the competition if they beat [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in their last group game, but a 1\u20130 defeat saw them crash out.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=112\u2013114}}\n\nDespite this indifferent performance, the English football establishment made no changes in policy, maintaining that England remained the best in the world and had simply fallen victim to bad luck in Brazil.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=112\u2013114}} Ramsey remained a central figure in the team, and captained his country against Wales on 15 November 1950 after Wright was left out due to poor form. Ramsey also captained England in a 2\u20132 draw against [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]] a week later\u2014the first time a team from outside the British Isles had played away against England and not lost.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=114\u2013116}} A year later, on 28 November 1951, England's unbeaten home record against overseas sides was challenged by [[Austria national football team|Austria]], then one of the most formidable attacking teams in Europe. The Austrians led 1\u20130 with 25 minutes to play, but were pegged back to 1\u20131 when Ramsey scored a penalty. The match finished 2\u20132\u2014England's unbeaten home record survived. The ''[[Daily Mail]]'' dubbed Ramsey England's \"ice-cool hero\";{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=118\u2013121}} he himself identified the Austria match in ''Talking Football'' as \"my greatest international\".{{sfn|Ramsey|1952|p=91}}\n\nRamsey remained in the England team throughout 1952, including in England's 3\u20132 win over Austria in Vienna on 25 May.<ref name=11v11international/>{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=121\u2013125}} After 29 consecutive international appearances he was left out of the squad for a match against Wales in October 1953 because of injury. He was reinstated for the following match later that month against a Rest of Europe XI, and scored his second international goal to secure a 4\u20134 draw.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=121\u2013123}} His last appearance for England came on 25 November 1953, in what the British press dubbed the \"[[Match of the Century (1953 England v Hungary football match)|Match of the Century]]\"\u2014England against the [[Football at the 1952 Summer Olympics|1952 Olympic]] champions [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]], the so-called \"[[Golden Team]]\" or \"Magical Magyars\", at Wembley Stadium.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=124\u2013127}}\n\nWhat British observers had forecast as a clash between two of world football's greatest powers turned into a walkover as England were beaten easily. The unbeaten home record was obliterated, along with any pretence that England had nothing to learn from overseas rivals\u2014they were totally outplayed by the fluid, fast-paced game of the Hungarians, which McKinstry comments was not dissimilar to Tottenham's push-and-run.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=124\u2013127}}{{sfn|Bowler|1999|pp=103\u2013105}} Ramsey scored a penalty, his third and final international goal, but Hungary, who had scored after less than a minute, won 6\u20133.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/1953/nov/26/newsstory.sport | title = Hungary's Famous Victory | first = Pat | last = Ward-Thomas | work = The Guardian | date = 26 November 1953 | accessdate = 22 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141215232144/http://www.theguardian.com/football/1953/nov/26/newsstory.sport | archive-date = 15 December 2014 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> He refused to accept that England had been outclassed, saying: \"Four of those goals came from outside the penalty area. We should never have lost.\"{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=124\u2013127}} Ramsey never played for England again, having won a total of 32 [[Cap (football)|caps]], scored three goals (all penalties),<ref name=halloffame/> and captained his country three times.<ref name=intapps50/>\n\n==Managerial career==\n\n===Ipswich Town===\n\nRamsey had made up his mind that he wanted to remain in football as a coach, but he had no relevant qualifications or managerial experience. While he spent the 1955 off-season coaching in [[Southern Rhodesia]], Ipswich Town of the Third Division South received permission from Anderson to speak to Ramsey about signing him as [[Player-coach|player-manager]]. When Ramsey met the Ipswich hierarchy on his return from Africa, he refused to combine management with playing. \"I told them I would only concentrate on one job\", Ramsey later said; \"it would be impossible to play with the players I would be coaching.\"{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|p=143}} This settled, Ipswich announced Ramsey's appointment as manager on 9 August 1955.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|p=143}}  Some of those who knew Ramsey had strong opinions about how he would manage. [[Wilf Grant]], a former Southampton teammate of Ramsey's who was now on the training staff at Ipswich, commented: \"He'll be good, but he will be the boss.\"{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|p=152}} Billy Wright, Ramsey's England teammate commented, \"In appointing Alf to become their manager Ipswich Town paid a tremendous tribute to intelligent football\u2014and footballers who think!\"<ref name=cobbolds>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.cobboldfht.com/features/feature1.php\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120207091151/http://www.cobboldfht.com/features/feature1.php\n| archivedate = 7 February 2012\n| title = Cobbolds and Ipswich Town Football Club\n| publisher = The Cobbold Family History Trust\n| accessdate =4 February 2013\n}}</ref>\n\nRamsey joined Ipswich just after the club's relegation from the Second Division at the end of the 1954\u201355 season, the team's only year above the third tier up to that point.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=143\u2013152}} To quote McKinstry, Ipswich had neither \"glittering pedigree or status\" nor \"strong footballing tradition\"\u2014the club had joined the Football League only in 1938, and its home ground at [[Portman Road]] was small and basic. One of the team's advantages was the patronage of the aristocratic [[Tolly Cobbold|Cobbold brewing family]], to which the chairman and much of the club hierarchy belonged.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=143\u2013152}} \"I had no plan for Ipswich when I went there\", Ramsey later said. \"In fact the first thing I had to do was to forget my set ideas on how football ought to be played. My experience had been in the First Division. I soon found that what I faced at Ipswich was very different.\"{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=143\u2013152}}  Ramsey kept most of the training staff hired by his predecessor [[Scott Duncan (footballer)|Scott Duncan]], who had stepped down after 18 years as Ipswich manager.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=143\u2013152}} Duncan stayed on as club secretary, meaning that Ramsey could concentrate on playing matters, leaving administration to Duncan.<ref>Bowler, pp. 120\u2013121.</ref>\n\nA relegated side with a number of players of \"mature age\", Ipswich were a tricky proposition for a new manager, especially as there was \"no money\" to improve the squad, so Ramsey worked to make the most of whatever talent he had inherited.<ref name=\"Winning Isn't Everything\">Bowler, pp. 117\u2013118.</ref> He made tactical innovations, noticed by the local newspaper: as early as his first game in charge he had his team taking three distinct styles of [[corner kick]], in a game where the side put on \"as poor a performance as one can recollect at Portman Road\".<ref name=\"Winning Isn't Everything\"/> In Ramsey's [[1955\u201356 in English football|first season]] as manager, he guided the club to third place in the Third Division South, with Ipswich scoring 106 goals in the 46 league games.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rsssf.com/engpaul/FLA/1955-56.html | title = Season 1955\u201356 | publisher = Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate = 30 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150924114623/http://www.rsssf.com/engpaul/FLA/1955-56.html | archive-date = 24 September 2015 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> During Ramsey's [[1956\u201357 in English football|second season]] in charge, he led the club to the division title, Ipswich again scoring in excess of 100 goals.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rsssf.com/engpaul/FLA/1955-56.html | title = Season 1956\u201357 | publisher = Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate = 30 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150924114623/http://www.rsssf.com/engpaul/FLA/1955-56.html | archive-date = 24 September 2015 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> It was Ipswich's second title at that level and it meant promotion to the Second Division,<ref name=\"IpswichTownHistory\">{{cite web | url=http://www.itfc.co.uk/club/history/ | title=Potted history of Ipswich Town F.C. | publisher=Ipswich Town F.C. | first=Jonathon | last=Ogle | date=16 February 2012 | accessdate=27 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141207231136/http://www.itfc.co.uk/club/history/ | archive-date=7 December 2014 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> and for the following three seasons, Ipswich managed to achieve mid-table finishes.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.statto.com/football/teams/ipswich-town/history |title = Ipswich Town Complete History |publisher = Statto Organisation| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418064114/http://www.statto.com/football/teams/ipswich-town/history | archivedate=18 April 2015| accessdate= 18 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1960\u201361 in English football|the 1960\u201361 season]], Ramsey guided Ipswich to the Second Division title and into the [[Football League First Division|top flight]] for the first time in the club's history.<ref name=\"IpswichTownHistory\"/> The success was built upon the prowess of [[Ray Crawford (footballer)|Ray Crawford]], the division's top goalscorer with 39.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engtops.html#1947-1 |title=Football League Div 1 & 2 Leading Goalscorers 1947\u201392 |publisher=RSSSF |accessdate=3 June 2016 |date=25 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628202228/http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engtops.html |archivedate=28 June 2011  }}</ref> The following season, Ramsey led his side to become [[List of English football champions|champions of England]] in their [[1961\u201362 Ipswich Town F.C. season|debut season]] at the top level.<ref name=\"IpswichTownHistory\"/> The side had been tipped by many contemporary football [[pundit]]s and journalists for relegation at the start of the season, making the achievement all the more remarkable.<ref name=\"Maxwell2013\">{{cite book|first=Tom |last=Maxwell|title=The Fabulous Baker Boys: The Greatest Strikers Scotland Never Had|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zqi8BQAAQBAJ&pg=PP95|year= 2013|publisher=Birlinn, Limited|isbn=978-0-85790-657-1|page=95|accessdate = 21 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Hardy2011\">{{cite book|first=Lance|last= Hardy|title=Stokoe, Sunderland and 73: The Story Of the Greatest FA Cup Final Shock of All Time|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fFb9q-zmsLMC&pg=PT10|year=2011|publisher=Orion|isbn=978-1-4091-1128-3|page=10}}</ref> Ramsey created a strong side based on a resolute defence and two strikers, [[Ray Crawford (footballer)|Ray Crawford]] and [[Ted Phillips (footballer)|Ted Phillips]] who between them scored more than 60 goals. The key to the side was considered to be [[Winger (association football)|left-winger]], [[Jimmy Leadbetter]] whom Ramsey moved into a deep-lying, left of centre [[midfielder]].<ref name=\"Banks2003\">{{cite book|first=Gordon|last= Banks|title=Banksy: The Autobiography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7lAccwoo_ZsC&pg=PT142|year= 2003|publisher=Penguin Books Limited|isbn=978-0-14-103932-9|page=142| accessdate = 21 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe following season started poorly for the league champions: Ramsey's former teammate Bill Nicholson changed the formation of his Spurs team to counter Ipswich in the [[1962 FA Charity Shield]] curtain-raiser to the 1962\u201363 season, a game which Tottenham won 5\u20131.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2011/aug/05/joy-of-six-charity-shield | title=The Joy of Six: Charity Shield matches | work=The Guardian | date=5 August 2011 | accessdate=26 August 2015 | author=Murray, Scott | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202003145/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2011/aug/05/joy-of-six-charity-shield | archive-date=2 February 2016 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The same season, Ramsey oversaw Ipswich's short-lived inaugural European campaign in the [[1962\u201363 European Cup]].<ref name=\"IpswichTownHistory\"/> Despite despatching Maltese club, [[Floriana F.C.|Floriana]], 14\u20131 on aggregate, Ipswich lost 4\u20132 on aggregate in the second round to the eventual winners [[A.C. Milan]], although Ipswich had won the home leg 2\u20131.<ref name=\"IpswichTownHistory\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/results/1962-11-28/ipswich-town-v-ac-milan | title=Ipswich Town 2 1 AC Milan | publisher=Statto Organisation | accessdate=7 September 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624002257/http://www.statto.com/football/stats/results/1962-11-28/ipswich-town-v-ac-milan | archivedate=24 June 2016 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Not long into the season, on 25 October 1962, Ramsey agreed to take charge of the England national team, commencing 1 May 1963.{{sfn|Bowler|1999|p=154}} He left Ipswich after eight seasons having guided them from the Third Division South to the top of English football.<ref name=ipswichstar>{{cite news | url=http://www.ipswichstar.co.uk/news/world_cup_medal_honour_for_sir_alf_1_173288 | title=World Cup medal honour for Sir Alf | work=Ipswich Star | date=26 June 2009 | accessdate=23 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924040602/http://www.ipswichstar.co.uk/news/world_cup_medal_honour_for_sir_alf_1_173288 | archive-date=24 September 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> After Ramsey's departure, Ipswich's performances declined and, two years after winning the league title, they dropped back into the Second Division.<ref name=fchd>{{cite web |url = http://www.fchd.info/IPSWICHT.HTM |title = Ipswich Town |publisher = fchd.info |work = Football Club History Database |accessdate  = 5 February 2008 |url-status = dead\n|archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100414041921/http://www.fchd.info/IPSWICHT.HTM |archivedate = 14 April 2010 |df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.soccerbase.com/league2.sd?competitionid=5&seasonid=93 |title = Final 1963/1964 English Division 1 (old) Table |publisher = [[Soccerbase]] |accessdate   = 16 March 2007 |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070810123403/http://www.soccerbase.com/league2.sd?competitionid=5&seasonid=93 |archive-date = 10 August 2007 |url-status = dead |df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===England===\nEngland lost to [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] in the quarter-final of the [[1962 FIFA World Cup|1962 World Cup]] in Chile and, being under attack from the British press,<ref name=shaw>{{cite news| url = https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-how-it-always-ends-in-tears-1068270.html| title = Football: How it always ends in tears| work = The Independent| accessdate = 21 September 2010| date = 2 February 1999| author = Phil Shaw| location = London| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121109032953/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-how-it-always-ends-in-tears-1068270.html| archive-date = 9 November 2012| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> manager [[Walter Winterbottom]] resigned five months later.<ref name=winterbottom>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1385263/Sir-Walter-Winterbottom.html |title=Sir Walter Winterbottom |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=20 March 2019 |date=19 February 2002 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160229032118/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1385263/Sir-Walter-Winterbottom.html |archive-date=29 February 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Although Ramsey's position as England manager was confirmed in October 1962, he formally took charge in May 1963,<ref name=fifa/> because Ramsey felt it would be wrong to walk out on Ipswich, who were struggling at the time.<ref>McKinstry, p. 199</ref> ''[[The Times]]'' reported that Ramsey had taken on \"a vulnerable position\" out of duty, but that he had delayed taking up his role due to Ipswich being \"engaged in the European Cup but also facing a struggle\u2014through injuries and other factors\u2014at the wrong end of the League table\", with hope expressed that he would take up the reins \"from the new year\".<ref>{{Cite news| date=26 October 1962| title=Ramsey Appointed As New England Manager|| url = https://www.thetimes.co.uk/archive/article/1962-10-26/3/2.html| work = The Times| accessdate = 21 March 2019}}</ref> When Ramsey took over as manager, he demanded complete control over squad selections: previously Winterbottom had been manager, but selections and other decisions were often carried out by board committees. Ramsey's appointment and his appropriation of all such responsibilities led to him being referred to as \"England's first proper manager\".<ref>{{Cite book | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=RmK5BAAAQBAJ&pg=PT33 | first = Andy |last = Groom | title = England's World Cup Story | page = 33 | publisher = Apex Publishing Limited |isbn=978-1-908582-55-3| year= 2011| accessdate = 21 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn appointment, Ramsey immediately caused a stir when he predicted \"we will win the World Cup\", which was to be hosted in England in 1966.<ref name=fifa/> One of Ramsey's first actions as England manager was to name the West Ham United captain [[Bobby Moore]] as captain of the national team.{{sfn|Dickinson|2014|p=61}} Moore came from working-class roots in the [[East End of London]], similar to Ramsey.{{sfn|Dickinson|2014|p=71}} England had never had a captain so young\u2014Moore was only 22 years and 47 days old when he captained the side for the first time, away against [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] in a [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly]] on 29 May 1963. England won 4\u20132.{{sfn|Dickinson|2014|p=61}}\n\n====1964 European Championship====\nRamsey's first competitive match as England coach was a [[1964 European Nations' Cup qualifying#Preliminary round|preliminary qualification round]] for the [[1964 European Nations' Cup]]. England, along with many other national teams, had declined to participate in the [[1960 European Nations' Cup|inaugural 1960 competition]]. They had been drawn against [[France national football team|France]] for a two-legged knockout fixture to progress to the last sixteen qualifiers. The home leg, played under Winterbottom, had been drawn 1\u20131 at [[Hillsborough Stadium|Hillsborough]].<ref name=firstgame>{{cite web | url=http://www.thefa.com/news/england/2015/feb/sir-alf-ramseys-first-england-game | title=On This Day: Sir Alf's first game in charge of England | publisher=The Football Association | accessdate=23 August 2015}}</ref> Ramsey insisted that he pick the team himself and included seven players who would feature in the 1966 World Cup squad. He took charge for the away leg in Paris at the [[Parc des Princes]], which they lost 5\u20132, eliminating England from the competition in Ramsey's first game in charge.<ref name=firstgame/>\n\n====1966 World Cup====\nAs hosts, England automatically qualified for the [[1966 FIFA World Cup|1966 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.skysports.com/football/news/12016/11385273/world-cups-remembered-england-1966| publisher = Sky Sports| title = World Cups remembered: England 1966| first = Stephen| last = Joyce| date = 7 June 2018| accessdate = 21 March 2019| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180726022730/http://www.skysports.com/football/news/12016/11385273/world-cups-remembered-england-1966| archive-date = 26 July 2018| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> The first group game, on 11 July 1966, was against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] and despite attacking talent, including [[Jimmy Greaves]] and [[Roger Hunt]], playing against a disciplined Uruguayan defence, England were held to a 0\u20130 draw. This was the first time England had failed to score at Wembley since 1945.<ref name=\"Uruguay196600\">{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/england/10908786/England-v-Uruguay-history-1966-Hosts-held-to-goalless-draw-on-the-way-to-winning-the-World-Cup.html | title=England v Uruguay history 1966: Hosts held to goalless draw on the way to winning the World Cup | work=The Daily Telegraph | accessdate=26 August 2015 | author=Saunders, Donald | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926020959/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/england/10908786/England-v-Uruguay-history-1966-Hosts-held-to-goalless-draw-on-the-way-to-winning-the-World-Cup.html | archive-date=26 September 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Ramsey's statement made three years earlier looked doubtful, but he remained calm and continued experimenting when his side faced [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] in the next game. Ramsey was using the [[4-3-3|4\u20133\u20133]] system and for each of the group games used a winger; [[John Connelly (footballer)|John Connelly]] against Uruguay, [[Terry Paine]] against Mexico and [[Ian Callaghan]] against France.<ref>{{Cite book | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dnTRzl3Uoe4C&pg=PT95&lpg=PT95#v=onepage&q&f=false | title = John Giles: A Football Man \u2013 My Autobiography | first = John | last = Giles | accessdate = 6 April 2017 | page=95 | year= 2011 | publisher = Hodder Paperbacks | isbn=978-1-444-72097-6}}</ref>\n[[File:Jimmy Greaves and Bobby Charlton.jpg|thumb|left|[[Jimmy Greaves]] ''(left)'' and [[Bobby Charlton]]. It was an injury to Greaves that brought [[Geoff Hurst]] into the England team. (1964)]]\n\nRamsey dropped [[Alan Ball Jr.|Alan Ball]] and John Connelly and brought in Terry Paine and [[Martin Peters]], whose advanced style of play as a midfielder matched the qualities Ramsey looked for in his system. England beat Mexico 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.11v11.com/matches/england-v-mexico-16-july-1966-229452/ | title=England v Mexico, 16 July 1966 | work=www.11v11.com | publisher=Association of Football Statisticians | location=London | accessdate=26 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160225101055/http://www.11v11.com/matches/england-v-mexico-16-july-1966-229452/ | archive-date=25 February 2016 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Ramsey replaced Terry Paine with Ian Callaghan for their final group match, against France. England won 2\u20130, securing qualification to the knockout rounds.<ref>{{Cite book | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=z4FBBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT99#v=onepage&q&f=false | page = 99 | title = Bobby Moore: The Definitive Biography | first= Jeff | last = Powell | accessdate = 6 April 2017| publisher = The Robson Press  |year=2014| isbn=978-1849547390}}</ref> Two difficult situations arose from the final group match. After making a vicious tackle and being cautioned, midfielder [[Nobby Stiles]] came under fire from senior FIFA officials, who called for Ramsey to drop him from the side. Ramsey strongly disagreed, and told the FA to inform FIFA that either Stiles would remain in his team or Ramsey himself would resign.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-england-at-the-world-cup-1966-england-the-day-alf-ramsey-stood-by-his-hard-man-1162621.html | work = The Independent | title = Football: England at the World Cup: 1966 England \u2013 The day Alf Ramsey stood by his hard man | first = Ken | last = Jones | date = 2 June 1998 | accessdate = 6 April 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170407060151/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-england-at-the-world-cup-1966-england-the-day-alf-ramsey-stood-by-his-hard-man-1162621.html | archive-date = 7 April 2017 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Another bad tackle was committed during that match, resulting in Tottenham striker (and one of England's most prolific goal-scorers) Greaves being injured and sidelined for the next few matches. Despite having more experienced strikers in his squad, Ramsey selected young [[Geoff Hurst]] as Greaves's replacement, seeing potential in the young West Ham forward.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/rapid-rise-of-hurst-shows-nobody-is-a-certainty-9150811.html | work = The Independent | title = Rapid rise of Hurst shows nobody is a certainty | date = 14 February 2002 | first = Ken | last = Jones | accessdate = 6 April 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170407060042/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/rapid-rise-of-hurst-shows-nobody-is-a-certainty-9150811.html | archive-date = 7 April 2017 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> The France match also marked Ramsey's final game with a winger. After it, he dropped Ian Callaghan from his side and brought back Alan Ball to strengthen the midfield.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/sport/3861865.Terry_Paine_s_biography_serialisation___part_two/ | title = Terry Paine's biography serialisation \u2013 part two | date = 19 November 2008 | work = [[Southern Daily Echo]] | accessdate = 6 April 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170407143508/http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/sport/3861865.Terry_Paine_s_biography_serialisation___part_two/ | archive-date = 7 April 2017 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Argentina 1966 rattin.jpg|thumb|[[Argentina national football team|Argentina]]'s [[Antonio Ratt\u00edn]] ''(striped shirt, left)'' is sent off during the [[1966 FIFA World Cup|1966 World Cup]] quarter-final against Ramsey's England.]]\nFor the knockout stages, England's first opponents were [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]]. Ramsey decided to switch from [[Formation (association football)|4\u20133\u20133]] to 4\u20133\u20131\u20132. With Ball and Peters operating on the flanks, the midfield now boasted Nobby Stiles and Bobby Charlton in the centre, indeed Ramsey refused a demand from the FA that he drop Stiles, making it a resignation issue.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/fifty-years-was-englands-1966-winning-xi-destiny-fate-or-a-chance-affair | title = Fifty years on: Was England's 1966 winning XI destiny, fate, or a chance affair? | first = Paul | last = Simpson | accessdate = 7 March 2018 | date = 29 July 2016 | work = [[FourFourTwo]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181214112023/https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/fifty-years-was-englands-1966-winning-xi-destiny-fate-or-a-chance-affair | archive-date = 14 December 2018 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> After a violent quarter-final (where the Argentinian captain [[Antonio Ratt\u00edn]] refused to leave the field after being sent off), England won 1\u20130 thanks to Hurst latching onto a cross from Martin Peters and heading home a goal. Ramsey came under fire when he stopped his players from the traditional swapping of shirts with the Argentinians in protest at their play and was then reported to have described Argentinian players as \"animals\"; \"It seemed a pity so much Argentinian talent is wasted. Our best football will come against the right type of opposition\u2014a team who come to play football, and not act as animals.\"<ref name=ipswichstar/> Jimmy Greaves in his 2009 autobiography, ''Greavsie'', claims that Ramsey had said \"I've been a little disappointed that the behaviour of some players in this competition reminded me of animals\". The belief that he had referred directly to the Argentinians as animals damaged Ramsey's reputation and made successive England teams unpopular abroad, particularly in South America.<ref name=\"Greaves2009\">{{cite book|first=Jimmy|last= Greaves|title=Greavsie: The Autobiography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zWwEdCVLD00C&pg=PA1813|year= 2009|publisher=Little, Brown Book Group|isbn=978-0-7481-1338-5|page=1813}}</ref> In the semi-final, England faced a fluent and skilful [[Portugal national football team|Portuguese side]] containing the tournament's top goal-scorer [[Eus\u00e9bio]]. However, England won a 2\u20131 victory in a memorable match which saw them concede their first goal of the competition from the penalty spot.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2004/jun/24/euro2004.sport1 | title=Nineteen sixty-six and all that \u2013 two Bobby Charlton goals to one by Eusebio | work=The Guardian | date=24 June 2004 | accessdate=28 August 2015 | last=Barham | first=Albert | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004042838/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2004/jun/24/euro2004.sport1 | archive-date=4 October 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 30 July 1966, Ramsey's promise was fulfilled as England became the World Champions by beating [[Germany national football team|West Germany]] in the [[1966 FIFA World Cup Final|final]].<ref name=\"CloakeRadnedge2010\">{{cite book|first1=Martin |last1=Cloake|first2=Aidan |last2=Radnedge|first3=Adam|last3= Powley|first4=Catherine |last4=Saunders|first5=Mark|last5= Hillsdon|title=Football The Ultimate Guide: Updated 2010 Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7QtUgJPE7aQC&pg=PA38|year= 2010|publisher=Dorling Kindersley Limited|isbn=978-1-4053-5171-3|page=38|access-date=10 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406024611/https://books.google.com/books?id=7QtUgJPE7aQC&pg=PA38|archive-date=6 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> A lot of Ramsey's tactics and decisions proved their worth in this final. Ramsey came under pressure to restore the fit-again Jimmy Greaves to the side,{{sfn|Hutchinson|2006|p=56}} but his philosophy was \"never change a winning team\".<ref name=ipswichstar/> He stuck to his guns and kept faith with Greaves's replacement, Geoff Hurst, who vindicated Ramsey's judgement by scoring a hat-trick in a 4\u20132 win (after extra time, the game ending 2\u20132 in regular time) at Wembley. Filling his side with a good balance of experience and youth proved vital when the gruelling final went to extra time. The youth in the team powered England through extra time, in particular Alan Ball who, at 21, was the youngest player in the England side. Even in extra time, he showed no signs of tiring and never stopped running\u2014famously setting up Hurst's controversial second goal, as well as having a few chances himself. Even as the match ended with Hurst scoring England's fourth goal, Ball was still running down the pitch in case Hurst needed assistance. Rather than a cross from Hurst, Ball was greeted by a number of England fans running onto the pitch who, thinking that the game was already over, had already started celebrating England's victory.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27378387 | title=1966 World Cup Final: Geoff Hurst scores final goal | publisher=BBC Sport | date=30 May 2014 | accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nHurst recalled that at the end of 90 minutes, Ramsey forbade his players to lie down on the pitch to rest before extra time, as their opponents were doing. \"Look at them\", Ramsey told the England team, pointing towards the Germans; \"They're finished. They're flat out on their backs.\"{{sfn|Hurst|2002|p=12}} Ramsey said to his players: \"You've won it once. Now you'll have to go out there and win it again.\"<ref name=fifa/>{{#tag:ref|The exact wording differs slightly between sources. In Hurst's autobiography, published in 2001, it is stated that Ramsey \"told us that we'd won it once. 'Now go and win it again,' he said.\"{{sfn|Hurst|2002|p=12}}|group=\"n\"|name=\"gowinitagain\"}}\n\n[[File:The Queen presents the 1966 World Cup to England Captain, Bobby Moore. (7936243534).jpg|thumb|[[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] presents the World Cup to the captain of Ramsey's England team, [[Bobby Moore]].]]\nRamsey remained his usual self during the celebrations: not joining in, but rather opting to let his players soak up their achievement.{{sfn|Hurst|2002|p=4}}  He is the only England manager ever to have won the World Cup. [[Bobby Charlton]] praised Ramsey and his approach to managing the England team to World Cup victory: \"He was professional to his fingertips and as popular with the players as any manager I've ever seen. He was a winner and without Alf Ramsey England would not have won the World Cup in 1966. He gave us our proudest moment.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.leaguemanagers.com/managers/sir-alf-ramsey/ | publisher = [[League Managers Association]] | title = Sir Alf Ramsey | accessdate = 21 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160305191412/http://www.leaguemanagers.com/managers/sir-alf-ramsey/ | archive-date = 5 March 2016 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Nobby Stiles agreed: \"You did it, Alf, we'd have been nothing without you.\"<ref name=glanville>{{cite web | title = Sir Alf Ramsey | work = The Guardian | url = https://www.theguardian.com/news/1999/may/01/guardianobituaries.brianglanville | date = 1 May 1999 | first = Brian | last = Glanville | accessdate = 22 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150910195134/http://www.theguardian.com/news/1999/may/01/guardianobituaries.brianglanville | archive-date = 10 September 2015 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n====1968 European Championship====\nIn 1967, a year after England won the World Cup under his management, Ramsey received a knighthood\u2014the first given to a football manager.{{sfn|Cox|Russell|Vamplew|2002|p=195}} England reached the last eight of the [[UEFA Euro 1968|1968 European Championships]] by amassing the best aggregate record of the four Home Nations over the [[1966\u201367 British Home Championship|1966\u201367]] and [[1967\u201368 British Home Championship|1967\u201368 seasons]] (despite a loss to Scotland 3\u20132 at home in 1967). They subsequently defeated Spain home and away to become one of four teams to progress to the finals in Italy. There England suffered a 1\u20130 defeat by Yugoslavia in a bad-tempered semi-final:<ref name=\"BBC68\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/sport/euro2000/history/1968_england.stm | title=Euro 2000:Fans Guide History of the Championship 1968 | publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate=25 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306183504/http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/sport/euro2000/history/1968_england.stm | archive-date=6 March 2016 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Alan Mullery]] was dismissed for kicking an opponent in the groin. Mullery subsequently reported that Ramsey had said to him \"I'm glad somebody retaliated against those bastards\" and paid Mullery's \u00a350 fine levied by the Football Association.<ref name=mullery>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17899534 | title = Euro 1968: Alan Mullery's moment of madness | first = Sam | last = Sheringham | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 12 May 2012 | accessdate = 22 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150506075818/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17899534 | archive-date = 6 May 2015 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> England had to settle for third place after beating the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]].<ref name=mullery/>\n\n====1970 World Cup====\n[[File:Anefo 922-9422 Peter Bonetti, Bobby Moore, Amsterdam 05.11.1969.jpg|thumb|Ramsey blamed the goalkeeper [[Peter Bonetti]] ''(centre, holding ball)'' for England's defeat to West Germany. (1970)]]\nEngland qualified automatically as defending champions for the [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970 World Cup]], held in Mexico. They entered the tournament as one of the favourites and many experts suspected that England and Brazil, due to meet in the opening round of matches, would meet again in the final.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/jonathanstevenson/2010/05/the_story_of_the_1970_world_cu.html| publisher = BBC Sport| first = Jonathan| last = Stevenson| accessdate = 7 March 2019| date = 12 May 2010| title = The story of the 1970 World Cup| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180727195617/http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/jonathanstevenson/2010/05/the_story_of_the_1970_world_cu.html| archive-date = 27 July 2018| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> Ramsey's preparations for the tournament had been disrupted by the arrest of Bobby Moore in the [[Bogot\u00e1 Bracelet]] incident with the England squad being labelled \"thieves and drunks\" by the Mexican press.<ref name=\"wc1970\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4850280.stm | title=World Cup history \u2013 Mexico 1970 | publisher=BBC Sport | date=27 April 2006 | accessdate=23 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060620044944/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4850280.stm | archive-date=20 June 2006 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn the first round, two 1\u20130 victories over [[Romania national football team|Romania]] and [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] enabled England to progress, despite a loss by the same scoreline to ultimate champions [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] (a match which also featured a famous save by [[Gordon Banks]] from [[Pel\u00e9]]'s header).<ref name=wc1970/>  In the quarter-final they lost to West Germany 3\u20132, after having been in the lead 2\u20130 with twenty minutes remaining.<ref name=wc1970/> At 2\u20131 Ramsey had substituted Bobby Charlton and [[Martin Peters]], supposedly to rest them for the semi-final, in what was considered a tactical blunder.<ref name=wc1970/><ref name=\"BBCwc1970\">{{cite web | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/history/newsid_1753000/1753266.stm | title=Germans turn tide against England | publisher=BBC Sport | date=4 April 2002 | accessdate=23 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907215439/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/history/newsid_1753000/1753266.stm | archive-date=7 September 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The blame for the defeat was partly placed on Ramsey's cautious tactics and substitutions in searing Mexican heat and partly on the stand-in goalkeeper, [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]'s [[Peter Bonetti]]. At 2\u20130 up Bonetti, who was playing because regular keeper Gordon Banks had been taken ill, had let a seemingly innocuous shot by [[Franz Beckenbauer]] slip under his body and was then caught out of position by a looping header by [[Uwe Seeler]]. [[Gerd M\u00fcller]] scored a third in the 108th minute to knock England out. Ramsey blamed Bonetti and his mistakes, but his own tactics were not beyond reproach.<ref name=halloffame/><ref name=BBCwc1970/>\n\n====1972 European Championship====\nEngland reached the last eight of the [[UEFA Euro 1972|1972 European championship]] by topping their qualification group which also contained [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]], [[Greece national football team|Greece]] and [[Malta national football team|Malta]]. They dropped only one point in the qualification, in a 1\u20131 home draw with Switzerland.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/72e.html | title=European Championship 1972 | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] | accessdate=22 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701150050/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/72e.html | archive-date=1 July 2016 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> England then faced West Germany again in a match to be played over two legs, to determine who would progress to the finals (which would feature only four teams). A 3\u20131 home defeat at Wembley, followed by a scoreless draw in Berlin, meant that England were eliminated. The football played by England against West Germany was described by the journalist [[Hugh McIlvanney]] as \"cautious joyless football\" and as an indicator that the England era under Ramsey had run its course.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://observer.theguardian.com/englandfootball/story/0,9565,540394,00.html | title=Why Sir Alf should end this field warfare | work=The Observer | date=9 May 1972 | accessdate=22 August 2015 | author=McIlvanney, Hugh | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305011451/http://observer.theguardian.com/englandfootball/story/0,9565,540394,00.html | archive-date=5 March 2016 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> West Germany went on to win the competition by beating the Soviet Union 3\u20130 in the final.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1972/matches/round=186/match=3838/postmatch/report/index.html | title=M\u00fcller the menace in German masterclass | publisher=UEFA | date=3 October 2003 | accessdate=22 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230235459/http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1972/matches/round=186/match=3838/postmatch/report/index.html | archive-date=30 December 2013 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n====1974 World Cup====\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-N0716-0310, Fu\u00dfball-WM, VR Polen - Brasilien 1-0.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Jan Tomaszewski]] ''(centre)'' whose goalkeeping for [[Poland national football team|Poland]] helped to prevent England from qualifying for the [[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974 World Cup]]. (1974)]]\nEngland's qualification group for the [[1974 FIFA World Cup|1974 World Cup]], included just two other teams: [[Poland national football team|Poland]] and [[Wales national football team|Wales]].<ref name=1974quals>{{cite web | url = http://www.rsssf.com/tables/74qual.html | publisher = Rec.Sports.Soccer Statistics Foundation | accessdate = 22 August 2015 | title = World Cup 1974 qualifications | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160303213323/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/74qual.html | archive-date = 3 March 2016 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/74q.html | title=World Cup 1974 Qualifying | publisher=www.rsssf.com | accessdate=24 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304074907/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/74q.html | archive-date=4 March 2016 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> However the Poles, who had not qualified for a World Cup finals since 1938, were an improved team who would go on to finish third in the tournament.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/06/07/sport/football/football-euro-2012-poland/ | title=From clowns to Kings: When Poland (almost) ruled the soccer world | publisher=CNN | date=8 June 2012 | accessdate=24 August 2015 | author=Montague, James | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926100756/http://edition.cnn.com/2012/06/07/sport/football/football-euro-2012-poland/ | archive-date=26 September 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/poland-comes-third-1974-beating-brazil-232710757.html |title=Poland comes third in 1974 after beating Brazil |publisher=Yahoo |date=6 June 2014 |accessdate=24 August 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925092318/https://news.yahoo.com/poland-comes-third-1974-beating-brazil-232710757.html |archivedate=25 September 2015 |first=Pan |last=Pylas |first2=Anne-Marie |last2=Belgrave |url-status=dead }}</ref> A home draw with Wales, followed by a defeat in [[Chorz\u00f3w]], meant that England had to win their final match against Poland at Wembley in October 1973. Ramsey had asked for the Football League games to be postponed on the weekend before the game to assist England's preparations. This request was refused by Football League chairman, [[Alan Hardaker]] who said: \"It is a football match, not a war\".<ref name=\"MurrayWalker2008\">{{cite book|first1=Scott |last1=Murray|first2=Rowan|last2= Walker|title=Day of the Match: A History of Football in 365 Days|url=https://archive.org/details/dayofmatchhistor0000murr|url-access=registration |year=2008|publisher=Boxtree|isbn=978-0-7522-2678-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/dayofmatchhistor0000murr/page/301 301]|access-date=10 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nBefore the qualifier with Poland at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]], the [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] manager [[Brian Clough]] described Polish goalkeeper [[Jan Tomaszewski]] as a \"circus clown in gloves\".<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/oct/12/jan-tomaszewski-poland-clown | work = The Observer | title = Jan Tomaszewski: A man haunted for ever after being called a clown | first = Maciej | last = Slominski | date = 12 October 2013 | accessdate = 27 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150919084031/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/oct/12/jan-tomaszewski-poland-clown | archive-date = 19 September 2015 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Errors by [[Norman Hunter (footballer)|Norman Hunter]] and goalkeeper [[Peter Shilton]] and an inspired goalkeeping performance by Tomaszewski, who made many crucial, and sometimes unorthodox saves, meant that the match finished 1\u20131. Ramsey, always uncomfortable with the [[substitute (association football)|substitute rule]], was blamed for waiting until the 85th minute before bringing on [[forward (association football)|forward]] [[Kevin Hector]].<ref name=1974quals/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sportsjournalists.co.uk/the-giller-memorandum/poles-apart-the-night-me-and-keegan-dropped-a-clanger/ | title=Poles apart: night Keegan and I dropped a clanger | publisher=www.sportsjournalists.co.uk | accessdate=24 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924105453/http://www.sportsjournalists.co.uk/the-giller-memorandum/poles-apart-the-night-me-and-keegan-dropped-a-clanger/ | archive-date=24 September 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=England 1 \u2013 1 Poland (17 October 1973)|url=http://englandstats.com/matches.php?mid=476|publisher=englandstats.com|accessdate=11 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625072830/http://englandstats.com/matches.php?mid=476|archive-date=25 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The draw meant that England had tried and failed to qualify for a World Cup for the first time in the national team's history.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/24445822 | title = England v Poland 1973: When Clough's 'clown' stopped England | first = Chris | last = Bevan | publisher = BBC Sport | accessdate = 5 February 2019 | date = 14 October 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181024072513/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/24445822 | archive-date = 24 October 2018 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Sacking====\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = It was the most devastating half-hour of my life. I stood in a room almost full of staring committee men. It was just like I was on trial. I thought I was going to be hanged.\n |source = Ramsey<ref name=fifa>{{cite web | url = https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/coaches/coach=44549/ | title = Classic Coach: Alf Ramsey | publisher = FIFA | accessdate = 22 August 2015 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228040557/https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/coaches/coach=44549/| archivedate=28 December 2013}}</ref>\n |quoted = 1\n |width = 35%\n}}\nEngland, having won the World Cup in 1966, were now perceived to have failed in three successive tournaments. The disappointments of quarter-final exits from major tournaments in 1970 and 1972, had been followed by failing even to qualify for the 1974 World Cup. A few months after the draw with Poland which had meant failure to progress, Ramsey was sacked by the FA on 1 May 1974.<ref name=shaw/>\n\nIt is alleged that some of the FA's officials had long held grudges against Ramsey. The British journalist and author [[Leo McKinstry]] said \"England's most successful manager would have had a legacy fit for a hero had it not been for the malevolence of the FA chief [[Harold Warris Thompson|Harold Thompson]]\".<ref name=sins/> [[Alan Ball Jr.|Alan Ball]] described the treatment of Ramsey as \"the most incredible thing that ever happened in English football\".<ref name=sins>{{cite web | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/may/21/seven-deadly-sins-football-alf-ramsey-england | title = Hero cast aside \u2013 Sir Alf Ramsey, 1970s | first = Leo | last = McKinstry | work = The Guardian | date = 21 May 2009 | accessdate = 21 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150912012001/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/may/21/seven-deadly-sins-football-alf-ramsey-england | archive-date = 12 September 2015 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===After England===\nFeeling he needed \"a period of rest\", Ramsey returned to [[Ipswich]] to spend time with his wife. He became a director of sportswear manufacturer [[Gola (manufacturer)|Gola Sports]] and of a local building firm, but kept out of the public eye for 18 months or so. He then began watching Ipswich Town, and often acted as a television pundit.<ref name=Yallop0677>{{cite news |title=Sir Alf ready for a comeback |first=Richard |last=Yallop |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=4 June 1977 |page=19}}</ref> Speaking on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s ''[[On the Ball (UK TV programme)|On the Ball]]'' in February 1977, he was sharply critical of England's performance against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]], describing the players as \"poor individually\" and the team as \"completely disorganised\".<ref name=Pundit0277>{{cite news |title=Other football |newspaper=The Observer |location=London |date=13 February 1977 |page=27}}</ref> Asked if he had any sympathy for his successor, [[Don Revie]], he said that Revie did not want sympathy: \"Having accepted the post of England team manager he has to accept the responsibility of his position in exactly the same way as I did.\"<ref name=Pundit0277/> His attitude to the media mellowed. Interviewed in June ahead of a [[five-a-side football|five-a-side]] tournament between eight of the 1966 World Cup teams for a trophy named in his honour, Ramsey admitted that, having \"met so many more people, I know so much more about the world, and I'm so much more relaxed than I was three or four years ago\", and said he would consider a return to management.<ref name=Yallop0677/>\n\nHe had joined the board of First Division club Birmingham City in January 1976.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ramsey on the board |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=22 January 1976 |page=20}}</ref> When [[Willie Bell]] was sacked as manager in September 1977, Ramsey refused the offer to take his place on a permanent basis, but did agree to act as [[caretaker manager|caretaker]] until a successor could be found.<ref>{{cite news |title=Middlesbrough reject bid for Souness |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=9 September 1977 |page=18}}</ref> By early November, he had changed his mind. He resigned his directorship to take on the role of consultant, with a remit that covered not only day-to-day team management but also a wide-ranging responsibility for club affairs, to include the selection of Birmingham's next manager.<ref>{{cite news |title=Consultant role for Sir Alf |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=3 November 1977 |page=20}}</ref> His tenure lasted just four months. In February 1978, star player [[Trevor Francis]] was fined for giving newspaper interviews about his desire to leave a club he saw as lacking ambition,<ref>{{cite news |title=Francis: the million pound prisoner |first=Richard |last=Yallop |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=18 February 1978 |page=9}}</ref> and the board accepted Ramsey's recommendation to place him on the transfer list. Three days later, when the decision was reversed for fear of a backlash from supporters, Ramsey gave two weeks' notice to quit.<ref name=Armstrong0378>{{cite news |title=Sir Alf wanted to let Francis leave |first=Robert |last=Armstrong |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=9 March 1978 |page=22}}</ref><ref name=Times0378>{{cite news |title=Francis issue caused Sir Alf to quit |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=9 March 1978 |page=14}}<br>{{cite book |first=Pat |last=Van Den Hauwe |title=Psycho Pat \u2013 The Autobiography of Pat Van Den Hauwe: Legend or Madman |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MWUnHisXv8oC&pg=PT19 |year= 2012 |publisher=John Blake |isbn=978-1-85782-713-2 |page=19 |access-date=10 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406021643/https://books.google.com/books?id=MWUnHisXv8oC&pg=PT19 |archive-date=6 April 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref>{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=486\u2013487}} The club announced his resignation before the notice period ended, and reports attributed his departure to the recent 4\u20130 defeat by [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]. Ramsey was quick to deny any such link, insisting that he had \"never walked out on anyone\".<ref name=Armstrong0378/> Francis was sold less than a year later, in what became known as the first million-pound transfer.<ref>{{cite news |last=Briggs |first=Simon |title=The day Trevor Francis broke football's \u00a31m mark |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/nottingham-forest/4560618/The-day-Trevor-Francis-broke-footballs-1m-mark.html |accessdate=29 May 2016 |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=9 February 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150306063323/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/nottingham-forest/4560618/The-day-Trevor-Francis-broke-footballs-1m-mark.html |archive-date=6 March 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nThe team won ten of the matches for which Ramsey was in charge, drew four and lost twelve.<ref>{{cite web |title=Managers |url=http://www.bcfc-archive.freeserve.co.uk/managers.htm |website=The Birmingham City FC Archive |publisher=Tony Jordan |date=21 April 2002 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030410030300/http://www.bcfc-archive.freeserve.co.uk/managers.htm |archivedate=10 April 2003| accessdate = 10 April 2003}}</ref> Among the ten was a 3\u20132 away victory at [[Anfield]] against the reigning league and European champions, Liverpool, on 21 January 1978, which featured in a ''[[Birmingham Mail]]'' series on Birmingham City's \"30 great games\".<ref name=\"BrumMail\">{{cite news |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-30-great-games-180672 |title=Birmingham City 30 great games: Liverpool 2 Blues 3 \u2013 January 21st, 1978 |first=Brian |last=Halford |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=14 October 2012 |accessdate=6 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109023603/http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-30-great-games-180672 |archive-date=9 November 2017 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Aged 58 when he left Birmingham, this was Ramsey's last full managerial job, although he did also work as a technical adviser at Greek side [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]], during 1979\u201380.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/329537.stm | title = Sir Alf Ramsey: World Cup victor | publisher = BBC News | date = 30 April 1999 | accessdate = 22 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20040210034845/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/329537.stm | archive-date = 10 February 2004 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/grk80.html |title=Greece 1979/80 |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045443/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/grk80.html |archivedate=4 March 2016 | accessdate = 4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Managerial style===\nDuring his time at Ipswich, Ramsey began experimenting with a new style of play that would eventually lead to success in the World Cup and led to his England team being styled, \"The Wingless Wonders\". As natural wingers were not always known for their defensive qualities, Ramsey started dropping them in favour of attacking midfielders who could also drop back into defensive roles. This system proved revolutionary as it often baffled opposing full-backs, who would naturally expect to see a winger coming down the flank at them once the ball was kicked off: instead, the attacking midfielders and strikers were taking the ball through the middle of the defence and scoring. This style of play proved successful at Ipswich, but really showed its worth when England travelled to Spain to play a friendly with them before the World Cup. As [[Bobby Charlton]] remarked, \"The Spanish full-backs were just looking at each other while we were going in droves through the middle\". To win in Spain, who were the reigning European Champions, was rare for an English team and was evidence that Ramsey's techniques were working.<ref name=\"Orejan2011\">{{cite book|author=Jaime Orejan|title=Football/Soccer: History and Tactics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H0l2T7tLSiEC&pg=PA112|year=2011|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-8566-6|page=112| accessdate = 21 March 2019}}</ref>\n<!--\nA firm but fair manager, Ramsey was often regarded as difficult by the press. He ran a strict regime with his players and made sure that no-one felt that they enjoyed special status, star player or not. In May 1964, after a number of players failed to show up for a meeting in a hotel about a forthcoming tour, amongst them Bobby Moore, [[Jimmy Greaves]] and [[Bobby Charlton]], they eventually returned to their rooms to discover their passports left on their beds. His strict regime didn't suit everyone but the players with real talent and respect for the game responded well to them and had great respect for Ramsey. Very few of those who played for Ramsey spoke ill of him. In the preparations for the 1966 World Cup, Ramsey made sure that no player was confident of a place in the final 22, which resulted in players performing at their highest level. His decision to appoint a young Bobby Moore as captain also showed Ramsey's ability to see great potential in young players. Another one of his abilities was as a master tactician: a quality that he had first shown with his reading of the game as a player. When it came to tactics, Ramsey had revolutionary ideas.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}-->\n\nRamsey earned the respect of his players. He strongly supported [[Nobby Stiles]] when the FA leaned on Ramsey to drop Stiles from the 1966 World Cup quarter-final following a tackle on Frenchman [[Jacques Simon (footballer)|Jacques Simon]] in the previous game.{{sfn|Lawton|2003|pp=168\u2013170}}  After the final, at the banquet, with the players in one room and their wives forced to sit in an adjoining room, he excused his players early from the banquet to allow the players to join their wives after nearly four weeks apart.{{sfn|Lawton|2003|p=208}} In his manner with the players, he was \"usually equable\", but when his 1978 Birmingham City team produced a poor defensive display, \"he blew his top\"; the next game was a \"historic victory\".<ref name=\"BrumMail\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nRamsey was very sensitive about his personal background. He strove to mask his [[working-class]] Essex origins and to present himself as erudite and worldly, going so far as to adopt an accent that the journalist [[Brian Glanville]] called \"sergeant-major posh\".{{sfn|Dickinson|2014|p=71}} A widely held perception that Ramsey's accent had become more upper-class during his time as England manager fuelled speculation that he had received [[elocution]] lessons, and prompted constant joking from members of the England team who came from similar Essex or East London backgrounds, such as Bobby Moore and Jimmy Greaves.{{sfn|Dickinson|2014|p=71}} [[Rodney Marsh]], a forward from the East End who played in Ramsey's England team from 1971 to 1973, later said:\n<blockquote>\nAlf tended to speak in a very poncey plum-in-the-mouth way. It was all \"Oh hello Rodney and how are you?\". To me it was all complete bollocks.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/may/21/seven-deadly-sins-football-alf-ramsey-rodney-marsh | title = Marsh and Sir Alf | first = Rodney | last = Marsh | authorlink = Rodney Marsh | work = The Guardian | date = 21 May 2009 | accessdate = 27 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150910101725/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/may/21/seven-deadly-sins-football-alf-ramsey-rodney-marsh | archive-date = 10 September 2015 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIt was rumoured that Ramsey had [[Romani people|Romany]] (or \"gypsy\") ancestors.<ref name=teleobit/><ref>{{Cite book | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=1dQ4AAAAQBAJ&pg=PT47| page = 47| title = Bill Nicholson: Football's Perfectionist | first=Brian|last=Scovell|publisher=John Blake Publishing |year=2011|isbn= 978-1843586692| accessdate = 21 March 2019}}</ref> Ramsey was sensitive about the suggestion and, according to one anecdote, seethed with fury when Moore saw some Romany caravans and joked that the manager should \"drop in to see his relatives\".{{sfn|Dickinson|2014|p=71}} The football journalist Ken Jones related that on one occasion, when Ramsey perceived Moore and Greaves to be mocking his accent on the team bus, he said he would \"win the World Cup without those two bastards\".{{sfn|Dickinson|2014|p=71}}\n\nThroughout his career as a professional footballer and for years afterwards, Ramsey claimed to be two years younger than he really was{{sfn|Hutchinson|2006|p=11}}\u2014including in his ghosted autobiography, ''Talking Football'', published in 1952.<ref name=teleobit>{{cite web | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/7624023/Sir-Alf-Ramsey.html | work = The Daily Telegraph | title = Sir Alf Ramsey | date = 1 May 1999 | accessdate = 20 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150925102721/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/7624023/Sir-Alf-Ramsey.html | archive-date = 25 September 2015 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> This began when Ramsey first turned professional with Southampton during the Second World War. He told Southampton he was born in 1922 rather than 1920, reasoning that this might improve his career prospects and compensate for the years he had lost to the hostilities. He propagated this false age for over two decades, in press articles, his autobiography and ''[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who]]''{{sfn|Hutchinson|2006|p=11}}\u2014but not on official documents such as his marriage papers, in which he listed his true date of birth.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=70\u201375}} Only after his knighthood in 1967 did Ramsey reveal his true age, deciding that he could not lie to [[Debrett's]], publisher of ''Debrett's Peerage & Baronetage''.{{sfn|Hutchinson|2006|p=11}}\n\nRamsey married Rita Norris (''n\u00e9e'' Welch) at Southampton Register Office on 10 December 1951.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=70\u201375}} The union had been delayed for some years because of Rita's marriage to another man, Arthur Norris\u2014the law of the period dictated that she could not obtain a legal divorce from Arthur until three years after their separation in 1947, and could not remarry for another year after that. Ramsey kept the relationship secret to the extent that Tottenham knew nothing of it until days before the wedding.{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=70\u201375}} Rita changed her name to Victoria and was generally called \"Vic\" by Ramsey, who McKinstry records was a good stepfather to her daughter from her first marriage, Tanaya (usually called Tanya).{{sfn|McKinstry|2010|pp=70\u201375}} He was a [[Freemasonry|Freemason]] of Waltham Abbey Lodge from 1953 until 1981, when he resigned.<ref>Article \"The Beautiful Game\" by Patrick Kidd and Matthew Scanlan, published in \"Freemasonry Today\", No.11, Summer 2010</ref><ref name=\"mason\">\n{{cite news\n|url= http://woolton.westlancsfreemasons.org.uk/2215-anfield-lodge/\n|title= Anfield Lodge No. 2215\n|date= 15 October 2017\n|work= Woolton Group of Lodges and Chapters\n|access-date= 17 October 2017\n|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171017202938/http://woolton.westlancsfreemasons.org.uk/2215-anfield-lodge/\n|archive-date= 17 October 2017\n|url-status= live\n|df= dmy-all\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Retirement and death==\nAfter Ramsey's retirement from football management, he continued to live in [[Ipswich]]. He was somewhat reclusive but wrote occasional columns for newspapers.<ref name=glanville/> According to his obituary in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', \"he concentrated on his golf game and watching his Westerns.\"<ref name=teleobit/> He made regular trips to Wembley, including a visit in 1991 where he and some members of the World Cup-winning team were reunited prior to that season's [[1991 FA Cup Final|FA Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/329537.stm | publisher = BBC News | title = Sir Alf Ramsey: World Cup victor | date = 30 April 1999 | accessdate = 9 April 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20040210034845/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/329537.stm | archive-date = 10 February 2004 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nRamsey suffered a stroke on 9 June 1998, on the eve of the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]].<ref name=stroke>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/122044.stm| title = 1966 Cup hero Sir Alf hit by stroke  | date = 28 June 1998 | accessdate = 22 August 2015| publisher = BBC News}}</ref> Suffering from [[Alzheimer's disease]] and [[prostate cancer]], Ramsey spent three months in a general ward in [[Ipswich Hospital]].<ref name=\"illness and death\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/1999/may/06/newsstory.sport | title=Sir Alf departs a land unfit for heroes | work=The Guardian | date=6 May 1999 | accessdate=29 October 2015 | last=Keating| first= Frank | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305081259/http://www.theguardian.com/football/1999/may/06/newsstory.sport | archive-date=5 March 2016 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> He died less than a year later, in a nursing home, on 28 April 1999, at the age of 79 from a heart attack. He was buried in a private ceremony at Old Ipswich Cemetery on 7 May 1999.<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=9GdADwAAQBAJ&pg=PT109&lpg=PT109&dq=alf+ramsey+Old+Ipswich+Cemetery&source=bl&ots=dS0Qxl_l7g&sig=ACfU3U3m2XZcavqb9eiyluFCqgvaj_VPVA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwju3tbJ-sXoAhXKZc0KHSScB2sQ6AEwEnoECAsQLA#v=onepage&q=alf%20ramsey%20Old%20Ipswich%20Cemetery&f=false ''The Gaffer'']</ref><ref name=funeral>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/337694.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Private funeral for Sir Alf | date=7 May 1999| accessdate = 22 August 2015}}</ref> The location of the funeral in Ipswich rather than in London was regarded as a snub to the Football Association whose members Ramsey had never forgiven for his sacking from the England manager post in 1974.<ref name=\"FootballAssociationSnub\">{{cite web | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/335725.stm | title=Sir Alf accused of final 'snub' | publisher=BBC Sport | date=5 May 1999 | accessdate=7 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Alf Ramsey Statue Close brightened.jpg|thumb|upright|Statue of Ramsey at [[Portman Road]]. The southern stand at the ground is named in his honour. (2007)]]\nRamsey was made an inaugural inductee of the [[English Football Hall of Fame]] in 2002 in recognition of his impact on the English game as a manager. He became the first person to be inducted twice when, in 2010, he was included in the Hall of Fame as a player as well as a manager.<ref name=halloffame>{{cite web | url = http://www.nationalfootballmuseum.com/halloffame/sir-alf-ramsey | title = Sir Alf Ramsey | publisher = English Football Hall of Fame | accessdate = 22 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150906194017/http://www.nationalfootballmuseum.com/halloffame/sir-alf-ramsey | archive-date = 6 September 2015 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSir Alf Ramsey Way, formerly Portman's Walk, is a street running along the north side of Ipswich's [[Portman Road]] stadium, that was named after Ramsey shortly after his death in honour of his achievements as Ipswich Town manager. In 2000, a statue of Ramsey was erected on the corner of the street named after him and Portman Road, at the North Stand/Cobbold Stand corner of the stadium. The statue was commissioned by the Ipswich Town Supporters' Club after an initial idea by local fan Se\u00e1n Salter. On 31 March 2012, the South Stand at Portman Road was renamed to the Sir Alf Ramsey Stand.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-17563309 | title = Ipswich Town renames stand after Sir Alf Ramsey | publisher = BBC News | date = 30 March 2012 | accessdate = 31 March 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120403051514/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-17563309 | archive-date = 3 April 2012 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> In 2009, [[Fabio Capello]] inaugurated a statue, sculpted by [[Philip Jackson (sculptor)|Philip Jackson]], of Ramsey at Wembley.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/england/6484603/Fabio-Capello-to-unveil-Sir-Alf-Ramsey-tribute.html | title = Fabio Capello to unveil Sir Alf Ramsey tribute | date = 2 November 2009 | accessdate = 21 August 2015 | work = The Daily Telegraph | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150926021310/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/england/6484603/Fabio-Capello-to-unveil-Sir-Alf-Ramsey-tribute.html | archive-date = 26 September 2015 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> It is situated in the player's tunnel and, according to [[George Cohen]], \"it will remind every player to give their best out on the pitch.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/nov/06/fabio-capello-world-cup-dreams-alf-ramsey | title = Fabio Capello admits World Cup dreams at unveiling of Alf Ramsey bust | date = 6 November 2009 | accessdate = 24 August 2015 | work = The Guardian | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150910195014/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/nov/06/fabio-capello-world-cup-dreams-alf-ramsey | archive-date = 10 September 2015 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nWhile not everyone reveres Ramsey's managerial style, for example according to historian [[Frank McLynn]] \"he was a humourless bore and stifling tactician whose reputation rests on a single undeserved triumph\",<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2005/oct/02/features.sport12 | title = Heroes and villains: Sir Alf Ramsey | first = Frank | last = McLynn | authorlink = Frank McLynn | work = The Guardian | date = 2 October 2005 | accessdate = 27 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150912000034/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2005/oct/02/features.sport12 | archive-date = 12 September 2015 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Ramsey was listed in the ten best British managers ever in ''[[The Independent]]'',<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/the-ten-best-managers-in-british-football-1687119.html?action=gallery&ino=6 | work = The Independent | title = The best managers in British football | accessdate = 21 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150925214920/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/the-ten-best-managers-in-british-football-1687119.html?action=gallery&ino=6 | archive-date = 25 September 2015 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> and he is widely regarded as one of British football's all-time great managers.<ref name=funeral/><ref name=\"Smith2009\">{{cite book|first=Tommy|last= Smith|title=Anfield Iron|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SfOLe2AoFnEC&pg=PA12|year= 2009|publisher=Transworld Publishers Limited|isbn=978-0-553-81925-0|page=12|access-date=10 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428142955/https://books.google.com/books?id=SfOLe2AoFnEC&pg=PA12|archive-date=28 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/manchester-united/10043419/Alex-Ferguson-retires-Manchester-United-manager-can-claim-to-be-the-best-thanks-to-Aberdeen-achievements.html | title=Alex Ferguson retires: Manchester United manager can claim to be the best \u2013 thanks to Aberdeen achievements | work=The Telegraph | date=8 May 2013 | accessdate=30 August 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926023828/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/manchester-united/10043419/Alex-Ferguson-retires-Manchester-United-manager-can-claim-to-be-the-best-thanks-to-Aberdeen-achievements.html | archive-date=26 September 2015 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n\n=== As a player ===\n'''Tottenham Hotspur'''\n* [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] champions: [[1949\u201350 in English football|1949\u201350]]<ref name=factfile>{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/332701.stm | title = Sir Alf Ramsey factfile | publisher = BBC News | date = 30 April 1999 | accessdate = 21 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20030118180159/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/332701.stm | archive-date = 18 January 2003 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Football League First Division|First Division]] champions: [[1950\u201351 in English football|1950\u201351]]<ref name=factfile/>\n\n=== As a manager ===\n'''Ipswich Town'''\n* [[Football League Third Division South|Third Division South]] champions: [[1956\u201357 in English football|1956\u201357]]<ref name=\"IpswichTownHistory\"/>\n* [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] champions: [[1960\u201361 in English football|1960\u201361]]<ref name=\"IpswichTownHistory\"/>\n* [[Football League First Division|First Division]] champions: [[1961\u201362 in English football|1961\u201362]]<ref name=\"IpswichTownHistory\"/>\n* [[FA Community Shield|FA Charity Shield]] runners-up: [[1962 FA Charity Shield|1962]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.tmwmtt.com/page.php?page=matchReport&level=1&tablename1=extended_results&tablename2=results&levelname=First%20Team&day=11&month=8&year=1962&sequence=0 | publisher = Pride of Anglia| title= Ipswich Town (0) 1\u20135 (2) Tottenham Hotspur \u2013 Charity Shield 1962\u201363|accessdate = 27 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''England'''\n* [[FIFA World Cup]]: [[1966 FIFA World Cup Final|1966]]{{#tag:ref|At the time of the 1966 World Cup only the players on the pitch at the end of the final received medals. Ramsey, his non-playing staff and 11 out of the 22 England squad members thus did not get medals at the time. In June 2009, after FIFA retrospectively revised its medals policy, winners' medals were formally presented to the 1966 England coaching staff and those players who had not finished the final by the Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] at [[10 Downing Street]]. [[George Cohen]], one of the team's defenders, received Ramsey's medal on behalf of the former manager's family.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8093891.stm | title = World Cup 1966 winners honoured | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 10 June 2009 | accessdate = 22 August 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120327051226/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/8093891.stm | archive-date = 27 March 2012 | url-status = live  }}</ref>|group=\"n\"|name=\"medal\"}}\n* [[UEFA European Championship]] third place: [[UEFA Euro 1968|1968]]\n* [[British Home Championship]]: [[1964\u201365 British Home Championship|1964\u201365]], [[1965\u201366 British Home Championship|1965\u201366]], [[1966\u201367 British Home Championship|1966\u201367]], [[1967\u201368 British Home Championship|1967\u201368]], [[1970\u201371 British Home Championship|1970\u201371]], [[1972-73 British Home Championship|1972\u201373]]\n\n=== Individual ===\n* [[English Football Hall of Fame]] Inductee: 2002<ref name=halloffame/>\n* [[Ipswich Town F.C. Hall of Fame|Ipswich Town Hall of Fame]]: Inductee: 2011<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.eadt.co.uk/sport/ipswich-town/sir_alf_ramsey_inducted_into_ipswich_town_hall_of_fame_1_859827 | title = Sir Alf Ramsey inducted into Ipswich Town Hall of Fame | first = Elvin | last = King | work = East Anglian Daily Times| accessdate = 21 March 2014 | date = 9 April 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Berlin-Britz transmitter|Berlin-Britz]] Manager of the Decade (1960s)<ref name=\"berlin-britz\">{{cite web |url=https://www.upl.ua/ua/news/view/1428?id=1428|title=Messi and Ronaldo: Equal!|publisher=[[Ukrainian Premier League|UPL]] |date=8 November 2017|accessdate=25 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| last1                 = Banyas\n| first1                = Volodymyr\n| title                 = Berlin-Britz Greatest XI by Decade\n| issue                 = \u2116 88\n| publisher             = newspaper Ukrainskyi Futbol\n| publication-date      = 25 October 2013\n}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\nSource:<ref name=\"11v11stats\"/>\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]\n|[[1946\u201347 Football League|1946\u201347]]\n|[[Football League Second Division|Second Division]]\n|23||1||1||0||24||1\n|-\n|[[1947\u201348 Football League|1947\u201348]]\n|Second Division\n|42||5||4||0||46||5\n|-\n|[[1948\u201349 Football League|1948\u201349]]\n|Second Division\n|25||2||1||0||26||2\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!90!!8!!6!!0!!96!!8\n|-\n|rowspan=7|[[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]\n|[[1949\u201350 Football League|1949\u201350]]\n|Second Division\n|41||4||3||0||44||4\n|-\n|[[1950\u201351 Football League|1950\u201351]]\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|40||4||1||0||41||4\n|-\n|[[1951\u201352 Football League|1951\u201352]]\n|First Division\n|38||5||2||0||40||5\n|-\n|[[1952\u201353 Football League|1952\u201353]]\n|First Division\n|37||6||9||0||46||6\n|-\n|[[1953\u201354 Football League|1953\u201354]]\n|First Division\n|37||2||6||0||43||2\n|-\n|[[1954\u201355 Football League|1954\u201355]]\n|First Division\n|33||3||3||0||36||3\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!226!!24!!24!!0!!250!!24\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career total\n!316!!32!!30!!0!!346!!32\n|}\n\n===International===\nSources:<ref name=intapps50>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng-intres50.html |title=England \u2013 International Results 1950\u20131959 \u2013 Details |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925001521/http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng-intres50.html |archivedate=25 September 2012 |accessdate= 21 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=intapps40>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng-intres50.html |title=England \u2013 International Results 1940\u20131949 \u2013 Details |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925001521/http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng-intres50.html |archivedate=25 September 2012 |accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by national team and year\n|-\n! scope=col| National team\n! scope=col| Year\n! scope=col| Apps\n! scope=col| Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=6|[[England national football team|England]]\n! scope=row|1948\n||1||0\n|-\n! scope=row|1949\n||1||0\n|-\n! scope=row|1950\n||9||0\n|-\n! scope=row|1951\n||7||1\n|-\n! scope=row|1952\n||7||0\n|-\n! scope=row|1953\n||7||2\n|-\n!colspan=2 scope=row|Total\n||32||3\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n:''England score listed first, score column indicates score after each Ramsey goal.''<ref name=intapps50/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ International goals by date, venue, cap, opponent, score, result and competition\n|-\n!scope=col|No.\n!scope=col|Date\n!scope=col|Venue\n!scope=col|Cap\n!scope=col|Opponent\n!scope=col|Score\n!scope=col|Result\n!scope=col|Competition\n!scope=col|Notes\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|1\n|| 28 November 1951 || [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]], London, England || 18 || {{fb|Austria}} || 1\u20131 || 2\u20132 || [[Exhibition game|Friendly]] || Penalty\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|2\n|| 21 October 1953 || Wembley Stadium, London, England || 31 || Rest of Europe || 4\u20134 || 4\u20134 || Friendly || Penalty\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|3\n|| 25 November 1953 || Wembley Stadium, London, England || 32 || {{fb|Hungary}} || 3\u20136 || 3\u20136 || Friendly || Penalty\n|}\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\n|-\n!rowspan=2 scope=col|Team\n!rowspan=2 scope=col|From\n!rowspan=2 scope=col|To\n!colspan=5 scope=col|Record\n!rowspan=2 scope=col|{{abbr|Ref|Reference}}\n|-\n!{{abbr|P|Matches played}}!!{{abbr|W|Matches won}}!!{{abbr|D|Matches drawn}}!!{{abbr|L|Matches lost}}!!{{abbr|Win %|Win percentage}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" scope=\"row\"|[[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]\n|align=left|August 1955\n|align=left|April 1963\n{{WDL|369|176|75|118|decimals=1}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmwmtt.com/sql/managers/profile.phtml?&managerid=4|title=Alf Ramsey|publisher=Pride of Anglia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080304043352/http://www.tmwmtt.com/sql/managers/profile.phtml?&managerid=4|archivedate=4 March 2008|url-status=dead| accessdate = 4 March 2008}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" scope=\"row\"|[[England national football team|England]]\n|align=left|May 1963\n|align=left|May 1974\n{{WDL|113|69|27|17|decimals=1}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamMgr/Mgr_Ramsey.html|title=Sir Alf Ramsey|publisher=England Football Online|accessdate=28 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623020830/http://www.englandfootballonline.com/teammgr/Mgr_Ramsey.html|archive-date=23 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" scope=\"row\"|[[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]\n|align=left|September 1977\n|align=left|March 1978\n{{WDL|28|11|4|13|decimals=1}}\n|<ref>{{cite book|first=Tony|last=Matthews|title=Birmingham City: A Complete Record|publisher=Breedon Books|location=Derby|year=1995|isbn=978-1-85983-010-9|pages=213, 243}}</ref>\n|-\n!colspan=3 scope=row|Total\n{{WDLtot|510|256|106|148|decimals=1}}\n!\u2014\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* [[List of English football championship-winning managers]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Bowler\n| first = Dave\n| title = Winning Isn't Everything: A Biography of Sir Alf Ramsey\n| year = 1999\n| origyear=1998\n| location=London\n| publisher =Orion\n| isbn = 978-0-7528-2733-9\n| ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Chalk|first1=Gary|last2=Holley|first2=Duncan|last3=Bull|first3=David|title=All the Saints: A Complete Players' Who's Who of Southampton FC|year=2013|location=Southampton|publisher=Hagiology Publishing|isbn=978-0-9926864-0-6|ref={{SfnRef|C