{"title_page": "Shekha of Amarsar", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{Peacock|date=April 2020}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n[[File:Maharao shekha - Copy.jpg|thumb|A Portrait of Maharao Shekha ]]\n[[File:Maharao shekha statue.jpg|thumb|Maharao Shekha Statue in [[Sikar]]]]\n\n'''Maharao Shekha''' (1433\u20131488), was a chieftain in 15th-century India. The [[Shekhawati]] gets its name from him, comprising the districts of [[Sikar district|Sikar]], [[Churu district|Churu]] and [[Jhunjhunu district|Jhunjhunu]] in the present-day Indian state of [[Rajasthan]]. The descendants of him known as the \"Shekhawat\".\n\n==Birth==\nHe was born to the Firozabad chief Mokal singh at [[Amarsar]]. His parents, previously childless, are said to have sought the prayers of intercession(the action of saying a prayer on behalf of another) of the Muslim [[Pir (Sufism)|pir]] Shaikh Burhan, for whom Shekha was named. In due time shaikh burhan had an heir,who according to the injunctions of boorhan, was styled after his own tribe,Shekh. He directed that child should wear the buddea(a strings or threads) which, when laid aside , was to be suspended at the saint's [[Dargah|durgah]]; and further ,that he should assume the blue [[tunic]] and cap, abstain from [[Pig|hog's]] flesh and eat no meat\"in which the blood remained.\" He also ordained that at the birth of every Shekhawat male infant a goat should be sacrificed. These obligations religiously maintained by a couple of centuries. <ref name=\":03\">{{Cite book|last=James tod|first=|url=http://ndl.iitkgp.ac.in/document/eXlWV2YwcUJjMmk5NStkV1dBOWlUVmtoM2tNa2hCUFBxMlo0MGd1QzRiND0|title=Clear writing edition of -Annals & Antiquities of Rajasthan or the central & western Rajput states of India|date=1873|publisher= madras Higginbotham and co 165 mount road|year=1873|isbn=|location=|page=359}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Hooja|first=Rima|title=A History of Rajasthan|publisher=Rupa & Company|year=2006|isbn=9788129115010|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Coronation==\nMahaRao Shekha has succeeded as the head \u00a0of ''Nan and Barwada'' estate along with 24 more villages \u00a0at the tender age of 12 years \u00a0as a result of untimely death of his father Mokal Ji in V.S 1502; A.D 1445.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Singh Shekhawat|first=Thakur Surjan|title=Rao Shekha|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nMaharao Shekha, when he attained man's estate, greatly augmented the territory left by his father, and consolidated 360 villages under his sway,by conquest from his neighbours, when his reputation and power attracted the jealous notice of the lord paramount of amber. He was attached, but by the aid of the [[Pathans of Rajasthan|Punnee Pathans]] he successfully withstood the reiterated assaults of his suzerain. Up to this period they had acknowledged the amber prices as liege lords, and in token of alliance paid as tribute all the colts reared on the original estate. A dispute on this point was the ostensible cause(though subordinate to their rapid prosperity), which occasioned a total separation of the Shekhawat colonies from the parent state, until the reign of Sawai Jay Singh, submission and pecuniary relief from them. Shekha left a well-established authority to his youngest son Raimal.<ref name=\":04\">{{Cite book|last=James tod|first=|url=http://ndl.iitkgp.ac.in/document/eXlWV2YwcUJjMmk5NStkV1dBOWlUVmtoM2tNa2hCUFBxMlo0MGd1QzRiND0|title=Clear writing edition of - Annals & Antiquities of Rajasthan or the central & western Rajput states of India|date=1873|publisher= madras Higginbotham and co 165 mount road|year=1873|isbn=|location=|page=360]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Hooja|first=Rima|title=A History of Rajasthan|publisher=Rupa & Company|year=2006|isbn=9788129115010|location=|pages=}}</ref></br>\n\n==Death==\n[[File:Cenotaph (Chhatri) where maharao shekha died.jpg|thumb|Cenotaph (Chhatri) where maharao shekha died]]\nShekha died in the year V.S 1545;A.D 1488 fighting the Gaur Rajputs in the war of ''Ghatwa'' defending the modesty and self respect of a newly wed lady. Shekha breathed his breathed at ''[https://www.google.co.in/maps/place/Ralawata,+Rajasthan+305801/@26.4961205,74.5114275,8.79z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x396bf371788a9cc3:0x80af1f14a7424784!8m2!3d26.6861197!4d74.8580233 Ralawta].'' A [[cenotaph]](''Chhatri'') was built at the place where he died. A statue of Maharao Shekha was also inaugurated at the same place by then-President of India Smt. Pratibha Patil <ref>{{Cite book|last=Sinh|first=Ranbir|title=History Of Shekhawats|publisher=Publication Scheme|year=2001|isbn=8186782745|location=Jaipur|pages=}}</ref> [[File:Innorgration of maharao shekha statue.jpg|thumb|Inauguration of Maharao Shekha statue by Honorable [[President of India]] [[Pratibha Patil]]]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of Rajasthan]]\n*[[Rajput]]\n*[[Rajputana]]\n*[[James Tod]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shekha Of Amarsar}}\n[[Category:15th-century Indian monarchs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{Peacock|date=April 2020}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n[[File:Maharao shekha - Copy.jpg|thumb|A Portrait of Maharao Shekha ]]\n[[File:Maharao shekha statue.jpg|thumb|Maharao Shekha Statue in [[Sikar]]]]\n\n'''Maharao Shekha''' (1433\u20131488), was a chieftain in 15th-century India. The [[Shekhawati]] gets its name from him, comprising the districts of [[Sikar district|Sikar]], [[Churu district|Churu]] and [[Jhunjhunu district|Jhunjhunu]] in the present-day Indian state of [[Rajasthan]]. The descendants of him known as the \"Shekhawat\".\n\n==Birth==\nHe was born to the [[Kachhwaha]] chief Mokal singh at [[Amarsar]]. His parents, previously childless, are said to have sought the prayers of intercession(the action of saying a prayer on behalf of another) of the Muslim [[Pir (Sufism)|pir]] Shaikh Burhan, for whom Shekha was named. In due time shaikh burhan had an heir,who according to the injunctions of boorhan, was styled after his own tribe,Shekh. He directed that child should wear the buddea(a strings or threads) which, when laid aside , was to be suspended at the saint's [[Dargah|durgah]]; and further ,that he should assume the blue [[tunic]] and cap, abstain from [[Pig|hog's]] flesh and eat no meat\"in which the blood remained.\" He also ordained that at the birth of every Shekhawat male infant a goat should be sacrificed. These obligations religiously maintained by a couple of centuries. <ref name=\":03\">{{Cite book|last=James tod|first=|url=http://ndl.iitkgp.ac.in/document/eXlWV2YwcUJjMmk5NStkV1dBOWlUVmtoM2tNa2hCUFBxMlo0MGd1QzRiND0|title=Clear writing edition of -Annals & Antiquities of Rajasthan or the central & western Rajput states of India|date=1873|publisher= madras Higginbotham and co 165 mount road|year=1873|isbn=|location=|page=359}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Hooja|first=Rima|title=A History of Rajasthan|publisher=Rupa & Company|year=2006|isbn=9788129115010|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Coronation==\nMahaRao Shekha has succeeded as the head \u00a0of ''Nan and Barwada'' estate along with 24 more villages \u00a0at the tender age of 12 years \u00a0as a result of untimely death of his father Mokal Ji in V.S 1502; A.D 1445.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Singh Shekhawat|first=Thakur Surjan|title=Rao Shekha|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nMaharao Shekha, when he attained man's estate, greatly augmented the territory left by his father, and consolidated 360 villages under his sway,by conquest from his neighbours, when his reputation and power attracted the jealous notice of the lord paramount of amber. He was attached, but by the aid of the [[Pathans of Rajasthan|Punnee Pathans]] he successfully withstood the reiterated assaults of his suzerain. Up to this period they had acknowledged the amber prices as liege lords, and in token of alliance paid as tribute all the colts reared on the original estate. A dispute on this point was the ostensible cause(though subordinate to their rapid prosperity), which occasioned a total separation of the Shekhawat colonies from the parent state, until the reign of Sawai Jay Singh, submission and pecuniary relief from them. Shekha left a well-established authority to his youngest son Raimal.<ref name=\":04\">{{Cite book|last=James tod|first=|url=http://ndl.iitkgp.ac.in/document/eXlWV2YwcUJjMmk5NStkV1dBOWlUVmtoM2tNa2hCUFBxMlo0MGd1QzRiND0|title=Clear writing edition of - Annals & Antiquities of Rajasthan or the central & western Rajput states of India|date=1873|publisher= madras Higginbotham and co 165 mount road|year=1873|isbn=|location=|page=360]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Hooja|first=Rima|title=A History of Rajasthan|publisher=Rupa & Company|year=2006|isbn=9788129115010|location=|pages=}}</ref></br>\n\n==Death==\n[[File:Cenotaph (Chhatri) where maharao shekha died.jpg|thumb|Cenotaph (Chhatri) where maharao shekha died]]\nShekha died in the year V.S 1545;A.D 1488 fighting the Gaur Rajputs in the war of ''Ghatwa'' defending the modesty and self respect of a newly wed lady. Shekha breathed his breathed at ''[https://www.google.co.in/maps/place/Ralawata,+Rajasthan+305801/@26.4961205,74.5114275,8.79z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x396bf371788a9cc3:0x80af1f14a7424784!8m2!3d26.6861197!4d74.8580233 Ralawta].'' A [[cenotaph]](''Chhatri'') was built at the place where he died. A statue of Maharao Shekha was also inaugurated at the same place by then-President of India Smt. Pratibha Patil <ref>{{Cite book|last=Sinh|first=Ranbir|title=History Of Shekhawats|publisher=Publication Scheme|year=2001|isbn=8186782745|location=Jaipur|pages=}}</ref> [[File:Innorgration of maharao shekha statue.jpg|thumb|Inauguration of Maharao Shekha statue by Honorable [[President of India]] [[Pratibha Patil]]]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of Rajasthan]]\n*[[Rajput]]\n*[[Rajputana]]\n*[[James Tod]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shekha Of Amarsar}}\n[[Category:15th-century Indian monarchs]]\n", "name_user": "Ankityadav65", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shekha_of_Amarsar"}
